# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aesthetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The essay discusses a variety of topics and uses many metaphors and thought experiments to illustrate her points, particularly focusing on women's lack of free self-expression.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Her metaphor of a fish explains her most essential point, "A woman must have money and a room of her own if she is to write fiction".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] She writes of a woman whose thought had "let its line down into the stream".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] As the woman starts to think of an idea, a guard enforces a rule whereby women are not allowed to walk on the grass.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Abiding by the rule, the woman loses her idea.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The essay was based on two papers Woolf read on 20 and 26 October 1928 to two Cambridge student societies, the Newnham Arts Society at Newnham College and the ODTAA Society ("One Damn Thing After Another") at Girton College, respectively.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Elsie Duncan-Jones, then known as Elsie Phare, was the president of the Newnham Arts Society at the time and wrote an account of the paper, "Women and Fiction", for the college magazine, *Thersites*.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Woolf stayed at Newnham at the invitation of Pernel Strachey, the college principal, whose family were key members of the Bloomsbury Group.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] At Girton she was accompanied by Vita Sackville-West.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] It was published in 1929 as a book with six chapters.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Although *Three Guineas* (1938) is a work of non-fiction, it was initially conceived as a "novel–essay" which would tie up the loose ends left in *A Room of One's Own*.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] On 1 January 2025, *A Room of One's Own* entered the public domain in the United States.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The title of the essay comes from Woolf's conception that "a woman must have money and a room of her own if she is to write fiction".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The narrator of the work is referred to early on: "Here then was I (call me Mary Beton, Mary Seton, Mary Carmichael or by any name you please—it is not a matter of any importance)".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The two Marys were ladies-in-waiting to Mary, Queen of Scots; they – along with Mary Carmichael – are also characters in a 16th-century Scottish ballad, "Mary Hamilton", about a lady-in-waiting who is facing execution for having had a child with the King, a child she killed.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The essay examines whether women were capable of producing, and in fact free to produce, work of the quality of William Shakespeare, addressing the limitations that past and present women writers face.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Woolf's father, Sir Leslie Stephen, in line with the thinking of the era, believed that only the boys of the family should be sent to school.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In delivering the lectures outlined in the essay, Woolf is speaking to women who have the opportunity to learn in a formal setting.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] She moves her audience to understand the importance of their education, while warning them of the precariousness of their position in society.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In section 3 Woolf invents a fictional character, Judith, Shakespeare's sister, to illustrate that a woman with Shakespeare's gifts would have been denied the opportunity to develop them.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Like Woolf, who stayed at home while her brothers went off to school, Judith is trapped in the home: "She was as adventurous, as imaginative, as agog to see the world as he was.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] While William learns, Judith is chastised by her parents should she happen to pick up a book, as she is inevitably abandoning some household chore to which she could be attending.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Judith is betrothed, and when she does not want to marry, her father beats her, then shames her into the marriage.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] While William establishes himself, Judith is trapped by what is expected of women.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] She runs away from home to London, is harassed and laughed at when she tries to become an actor, and is finally made pregnant by an actor-manager who said he would help her.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] She kills herself and "lies buried at some cross-roads where the omnibuses now stop outside the Elephant and Castle".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] William lives on and establishes his legacy.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In the essay, Woolf constructs a critical and historical account of women writers thus far.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Woolf examines the careers of several female authors, including Aphra Behn, Jane Austen, the Brontë sisters, Anne Finch, Countess of Winchilsea, and George Eliot.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In addition to female authors, Woolf also discusses and draws inspiration from noted scholar and feminist Jane Ellen Harrison.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Woolf also discusses Rebecca West, questioning Desmond MacCarthy's (referred to as "Z") uncompromising dismissal of West as an "'arrant feminist'".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Among the men attacked for their views on women, F.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead (referred to as "Lord Birkenhead") is mentioned, although Woolf further rebukes his ideas in stating she will not "trouble to copy out Lord Birkenhead's opinion upon the writing of women".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The essay quotes Oscar Browning, through the words of his (possibly inaccurate) biographer H.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Wortham, "that the impression left on his mind, after looking over any set of examination papers, was that, irrespective of the marks he might give, the best woman was intellectually the inferior of the worst man".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Woolf wrote in her diary before *A Room of One's Own* was published that she thought when it was published she would be "attacked for a feminist & hinted at for a sapphist".
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In one section of the book, describing the work of a fictional woman writer, Mary Carmichael, Woolf deliberately invokes lesbianism: "Then may I tell you that the very next words I read were these – 'Chloe liked Olivia ...' Do not start.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Let us admit in the privacy of our own society that these things sometimes happen.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Sometimes women do like women." Woolf references the obscenity trial and public uproar resulting from the publishing of Radclyffe Hall's lesbian-themed novel *The Well of Loneliness* (1928).
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Before she can discuss Chloe liking Olivia, the narrator has to be assured that Sir Chartres Biron, the magistrate of Hall's obscenity trial, is not in the audience: "Are there no men present?
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Do you promise the figure of Sir Chartres Biron is not concealed?
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Farwell has shed light on the difficulty around understanding androgyny in Woolf's work.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Nancy Topping Bazin defines Woolf's concept of androgyny as "the masculine and feminine should be balanced but not fused." In her definition, Bazin reveals an important debate in understanding androgyny: whether to see it as a balance or fusion of two parts.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Some critics describe Woolf's concept of androgyny as a balance between various poles: intuition and reason, subjectivity and objectivity, anima and animus, heterosexuality and homosexuality, and manic and depressive.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Androgyny in a writer translates to accepting both intuition and rationality as a way to knowledge.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The interpretation of androgyny as balance would imply validating many voices and perceptions.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] On the other hand, seeing androgyny as a fusion would validate only a single mode of knowing.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Farwell argues that since "the universal is most often identified with whatever is male, this definition can be and has been another means for demanding that a woman write like a man." Farwell interprets Woolf's ambivalence in defining androgyny from fear of being called a feminist.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Alice Walker responded to Woolf's observation that only women with 'a room of their own' are in a position to write.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Woolf herself was making the point that not all women in her society had such a safe space, but Walker continues the conversation by discussing the further exclusions suffered by women of colour.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The essay was the inspiration for the Hosking Houses Trust set up by Sarah Hosking (arts administrator) in order to provide a quiet space for women creatives in the village of Clifford Chambers in Warwickshire, England.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] The fanfiction archive Archive of Our Own was named after the essay.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Patricia Lamkin's play *Balancing the Moon* (2011) was inspired by the essay.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In 2014, artist Kabe Wilson produced a novella and artwork entitled *Of One Woman Or So*, created over five years by rearranging the words of *A Room of One's Own*.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] Cultural ventures have been named after *A Room of One's Own*.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] In 1975 the Wisconsin bookstore A Room of One's Own was founded by five women as a feminist bookstore.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] A literary journal launched in Vancouver, Canada in 1975 by the West Coast Feminist Literary Magazine Society, or the Growing Room Collective, was originally called *Room of One's Own* but changed to *Room* in 2007.
[src:aesthetics/a-room-of-one-s-own] It was out of this line of thinking that "A Room of Her Own" emerged, building on Virginia Woolf's 1929 feminist text that argues for women's need for space to think and create".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning, unlike deductive reasoning, yields a plausible conclusion but does not definitively verify it.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abductive conclusions do not eliminate uncertainty or doubt, which is expressed in terms such as "best available" or "most likely".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] While inductive reasoning draws general conclusions that apply to many situations, abductive conclusions are confined to the particular observations in question.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In the 1990s, as computing power grew, the fields of law, computer science, and artificial intelligence research spurred renewed interest in the subject of abduction.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Diagnostic expert systems frequently employ abduction.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning allows deriving b from a only where b is a formal logical consequence of a .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In other words, deduction derives the consequences of the assumed.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Given the truth of the assumptions, a valid deduction guarantees the truth of the conclusion.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] For example, given that "Socrates is a man" ( $a_{1}$ ) and "All men are mortal" ( $a_{2}$ ), it follows that "Socrates is mortal" ( b ).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Inductive reasoning is the process of inferring some *general* principle b from a body of knowledge a , where b does not necessarily follow from a . a might give us very good reason to accept b but does not ensure b .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] For example, if all swans that a person has observed so far are white, they may infer a universal categorical proposition of the form *All swans are white*.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] They have good reason to believe the conclusion from the premise because it is the *best explanation* for their observations, but the truth of the conclusion is not guaranteed.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, it turns out that some swans are black.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning allows inferring a as an explanation of b .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] As a result of this inference, abduction allows the precondition a to be abducted from the consequence b .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning and abductive reasoning differ in which end, left or right, of the proposition " a entails b " serves as the conclusion.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] For example, with deductive reasoning, knowing that it rained heavily during the night, you could deduce that the lawn will be wet in the morning without looking outside.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] With abductive reasoning, a couple leaving their house in the morning and seeing that their lawn is wet might abduce that it rained while they were asleep.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] This serves as a hypothesis that "best explains" their observation.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Given the many possible explanations for the lawn getting wet, their abduction does not establish certainty that it rained overnight, but it is still useful and can serve to orient them in their surroundings.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Despite many possible explanations for any physical process we observe, we tend to abduce a single explanation (or a few) for this process in the expectation that we can better orient ourselves in our surroundings and disregard some possibilities.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Properly used, abductive reasoning can be a useful source of priors in Bayesian statistics.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] One can understand abductive reasoning as inference to the best explanation, although the terms *abduction* and *inference to the best explanation* are not always used equivalently.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In logic, explanation is accomplished through the use of a logical theory T representing a domain and a set of observations O .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the process of deriving a set of explanations of O according to T and picking out one of those explanations.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In formal logic, O and E are assumed to be sets of literals.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Among the possible explanations E satisfying these two conditions, some other condition of minimality is usually imposed to avoid irrelevant facts (not contributing to the entailment of O ) being included in the explanations.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is then the process that picks out some member of E .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Criteria for picking out a member representing "the best" explanation include the simplicity, the prior probability, or the explanatory power of the explanation.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] A proof-theoretical abduction method for first-order classical logic based on the sequent calculus and a dual one, based on semantic tableaux (analytic tableaux) have been proposed.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The methods are sound and complete and work for full first-order logic, without requiring any preliminary reduction of formulae into normal forms.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] These methods have also been extended to modal logic.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abductive logic programming is a computational framework that extends normal logic programming with abduction.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] It separates the theory T into two components, one of which is a normal logic program, used to generate E by means of backward reasoning, the other of which is a set of integrity constraints, used to filter the set of candidate explanations.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] A different formalization of abduction is based on inverting the function that calculates the visible effects of the hypotheses.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Formally, we are given a set of hypotheses H and a set of manifestations M ; they are related by the domain knowledge, represented by a function e that takes as an argument a set of hypotheses and gives as a result the corresponding set of manifestations.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In other words, for every subset of the hypotheses $H'\subseteq H$ , their effects are known to be $e(H')$ .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is performed by finding a set $H'\subseteq H$ such that $M\subseteq e(H')$ .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In other words, abduction is performed by finding a set of hypotheses $H'$ such that their effects $e(H')$ include all observations M .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] A common assumption is that the effects of the hypotheses are independent, that is, for every $H'\subseteq H$ , it holds that $e(H')=\bigcup _{h\in H'}e(\{h\})$ .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] If this condition is met, abduction can be seen as a form of set covering.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abductive validation is the process of validating a given hypothesis through abductive reasoning.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] This can also be called reasoning through successive approximation.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Under this principle, an explanation is valid if it is the best possible explanation of a set of known data.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The best possible explanation is often defined in terms of simplicity and elegance (see Occam's razor).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Subjective logic generalises probabilistic logic by including degrees of epistemic uncertainty in the input arguments, i.e. instead of probabilities, the analyst can express arguments as subjective opinions.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction in subjective logic is thus a generalization of probabilistic abduction described above.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The input arguments in subjective logic are subjective opinions which can be binomial when the opinion applies to a binary variable or multinomial when it applies to an *n*-ary variable.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Assume the domains $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ with respective variables X and Y , the set of conditional opinions $\omega _{X\mid Y}$ (i.e. one conditional opinion for each value y ), and the base rate distribution $a_{Y}$ .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Using these inverted conditionals together with the opinion $\omega _{X}$ subjective deduction denoted by the operator $\circledcirc$ can be used to abduce the marginal opinion $\omega _{Y\,{\overline {\|}}\,X}$ .
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The symbolic notation for subjective abduction is " ${\widetilde {\|}}$ ", and the operator itself is denoted as " ${\widetilde {\circledcirc }}$ ".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The operator for the subjective Bayes' theorem is denoted " ${\widetilde {\phi \,}}$ ", and subjective deduction is denoted " $\circledcirc$ ".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The advantage of using subjective logic abduction compared to probabilistic abduction is that both aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty about the input argument probabilities can be explicitly expressed and taken into account during the analysis.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] It is thus possible to perform abductive analysis in the presence of uncertain arguments, which naturally results in degrees of uncertainty in the output conclusions.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The idea that the simplest, most easily verifiable solution should be preferred over its more complicated counterparts is a very old one.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] To this point, George Pólya, in his treatise on problem-solving, makes reference to the following Latin truism: *simplex sigillum veri* (simplicity is the seal of truth).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The American philosopher Charles Sanders Peirce introduced abduction into modern logic.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Over the years he called such inference *hypothesis*, *abduction*, *presumption*, and *retroduction*.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] He considered it a topic in logic as a normative field in philosophy, not in purely formal or mathematical logic, and eventually as a topic also in economics of research.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] As two stages of the development, extension, etc., of a hypothesis in scientific inquiry, abduction and also induction are often collapsed into one overarching concept—the hypothesis.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] That is why, in the scientific method known from Galileo and Bacon, the abductive stage of hypothesis formation is conceptualized simply as induction.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Thus, in the twentieth century this collapse was reinforced by Karl Popper's explication of the hypothetico-deductive model, where the hypothesis is considered to be just "a guess" (in the spirit of Peirce).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] However, when the formation of a hypothesis is considered the result of a process it becomes clear that this "guess" has already been tried and made more robust in thought as a necessary stage of its acquiring the status of hypothesis.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, many abductions are rejected or heavily modified by subsequent abductions before they ever reach this stage.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Before 1900, Peirce treated abduction as the use of a known rule to explain an observation.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] For instance: it is a known rule that, if it rains, grass gets wet; so, to explain the fact that the grass on this lawn is wet, one *abduces* that it has rained.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can lead to false conclusions if other rules that might explain the observation are not taken into account—e.g. the grass could be wet from dew.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] This remains the common use of the term "abduction" in the social sciences and in artificial intelligence.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce consistently characterized it as the kind of inference that originates a hypothesis by concluding in an explanation, though an unassured one, for some very curious or surprising (anomalous) observation stated in a premise.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] As early as 1865 he wrote that all conceptions of cause and force are reached through hypothetical inference; in the 1900s he wrote that all explanatory content of theories is reached through abduction.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In other respects Peirce revised his view of abduction over the years.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In Peirce's *On the Natural Classification of Arguments* (1867), hypothetical inference always deals with a cluster of characters (call them *P′, P′′, P′′′,* etc.) known to occur at least whenever a certain character (*M*) occurs.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Note that categorical syllogisms have elements traditionally called middles, predicates, and subjects.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] For example: All *men* [middle] are *mortal* [predicate]; *Socrates* [subject] is a *man* [middle]; ergo *Socrates* [subject] is *mortal* [predicate]".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Below, 'M' stands for a middle; 'P' for a predicate; 'S' for a subject.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that all deduction can be put into the form of the categorical syllogism Barbara (AAA-1).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In 1878, in *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis*, there is no longer a need for multiple characters or predicates in order for an inference to be hypothetical, although it is still helpful.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Moreover, Peirce no longer poses hypothetical inference as concluding in a *probable* hypothesis.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In the forms themselves, it is understood but not explicit that induction involves random selection and that hypothetical inference involves response to a "very curious circumstance".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The forms instead emphasize the modes of inference as rearrangements of one another's propositions (without the bracketed hints shown below).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce long treated abduction in terms of induction from characters or traits (weighed, not counted like objects), explicitly so in his influential 1883 "A theory of probable inference", in which he returns to involving probability in the hypothetical conclusion.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Like *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis* in 1878, it was widely read (see the historical books on statistics by Stephen Stigler), unlike his later amendments of his conception of abduction.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Today abduction remains most commonly understood as induction from characters and extension of a known rule to cover unexplained circumstances.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Sherlock Holmes used this method of reasoning in the stories of Arthur Conan Doyle, although Holmes refers to it as "deductive reasoning".
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In 1902 Peirce wrote that he now regarded the syllogistical forms and the doctrine of extension and comprehension (i.e., objects and characters as referenced by terms), as being less fundamental than he had earlier thought.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The hypothesis is framed, but not asserted, in a premise, then asserted as rationally suspectable in the conclusion.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Thus, as in the earlier categorical syllogistic form, the conclusion is formulated from some premise(s).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] But all the same the hypothesis consists more clearly than ever in a new or outside idea beyond what is known or observed.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Induction in a sense goes beyond observations already reported in the premises, but it merely amplifies ideas already known to represent occurrences, or tests an idea supplied by hypothesis; either way it requires previous abductions in order to get such ideas in the first place.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Induction seeks facts to test a hypothesis; abduction seeks a hypothesis to account for facts.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Note that the hypothesis ("A") could be of a rule.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] It need not even be a rule strictly necessitating the surprising observation ("C"), which needs to follow only as a "matter of course"; or the "course" itself could amount to some known rule, merely alluded to, and also not necessarily a rule of strict necessity.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce did not remain quite convinced about any such form as the categorical syllogistic form or the 1903 form.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In 1911, he wrote, "I do not, at present, feel quite convinced that any logical form can be assigned that will cover all 'Retroductions'.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] It is a method for fruitful clarification of conceptions by equating the meaning of a conception with the conceivable practical implications of its object's conceived effects.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that that is precisely tailored to abduction's purpose in inquiry, the forming of an idea that could conceivably shape informed conduct.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In various writings in the 1900s he said that the conduct of abduction (or retroduction) is governed by considerations of economy, belonging in particular to the economics of research.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] He regarded economics as a normative science whose analytic portion might be part of logical methodeutic (that is, theory of inquiry).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Logical critic, or logic proper, on validity or justifiability of inference, the conditions for true representation.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Critique of arguments in their various modes (deduction, induction, abduction).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Methodeutic, or speculative rhetoric, on the conditions for determination of interpretations.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Methodology of inquiry in its interplay of modes.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce had, from the start, seen the modes of inference as being coordinated together in scientific inquiry and, by the 1900s, held that hypothetical inference in particular is inadequately treated at the level of critique of arguments.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] To increase the assurance of a hypothetical conclusion, one needs to deduce implications about evidence to be found, predictions which induction can test through observation so as to evaluate the hypothesis.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] That is Peirce's outline of the scientific method of inquiry, as covered in his inquiry methodology, which includes pragmatism or, as he later called it, pragmaticism, the clarification of ideas in terms of their conceivable implications regarding informed practice.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Induction is inference through an *index* (a sign by factual connection); a sample is an index of the totality from which it is drawn.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Deduction is inference through a *symbol* (a sign by interpretive habit irrespective of resemblance or connection to its object).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] At the critical level Peirce examined the forms of abductive arguments (as discussed above), and came to hold that the hypothesis should economize explanation for plausibility in terms of the feasible and natural.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In 1908 Peirce described this plausibility in some detail.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The phrase "inference to the best explanation" (not used by Peirce but often applied to hypothetical inference) is not always understood as referring to the most simple and natural hypotheses (such as those with the fewest assumptions).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] However, in other senses of "best", such as "standing up best to tests", it is hard to know which is the best explanation to form, since one has not tested it yet.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Still, for Peirce, any justification of an abductive inference as "good" is not completed upon its formation as an argument (unlike with induction and deduction) and instead depends also on its methodological role and promise (such as its testability) in advancing inquiry.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Here, considerations such as probability, absent from the treatment of abduction at the critical level, come into play.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Peirce indicated that abductive reasoning is driven by the need for "economy in research"—the expected fact-based productivity of hypotheses, prior to deductive and inductive processes of verification.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] A key concept proposed by him in this regard is "uberty"—the expected fertility and pragmatic value of reasoning.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] This concept seems to be gaining support via association to the Free Energy Principle.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Gilbert Harman was a professor of philosophy at Princeton University.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Harman's 1965 account of the role of "inference to the best explanation" – inferring the existence of that which we need for the best explanation of observable phenomena – has been very influential.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Stephen Jay Gould, in answering the Omphalos hypothesis, claimed that only hypotheses that can be proved incorrect lie within the domain of science and only these hypotheses are good explanations of facts worth inferring to.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Applications in artificial intelligence include fault diagnosis, belief revision, and automated planning.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The most direct application of abduction is that of automatically detecting faults in systems: given a theory relating faults with their effects and a set of observed effects, abduction can be used to derive sets of faults that are likely to be the cause of the problem.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In medicine, abduction can be seen as a component of clinical evaluation and judgment.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The Internist-I diagnostic system, the first AI system that covered the field of Internal Medicine, used abductive reasoning to converge on the most likely causes of a set of patient symptoms that it acquired through an interactive dialog with an expert user.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can also be used to model automated planning.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Given a logical theory relating action occurrences with their effects (for example, a formula of the event calculus), the problem of finding a plan for reaching a state can be modeled as the problem of abducting a set of literals implying that the final state is the goal state.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In intelligence analysis, analysis of competing hypotheses and Bayesian networks, probabilistic abductive reasoning is used extensively.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Similarly in medical diagnosis and legal reasoning, the same methods are being used, although there have been many examples of errors, especially caused by the base rate fallacy and the prosecutor's fallacy.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Belief revision, the process of adapting beliefs in view of new information, is another field in which abduction has been applied.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The main problem of belief revision is that the new information may be inconsistent with the prior web of beliefs, while the result of the incorporation cannot be inconsistent.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The process of updating the web of beliefs can be done by the use of abduction: once an explanation for the observation has been found, integrating it does not generate inconsistency.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In 1992 Peter Gärdenfors presented a paper which contained a brief survey of the area of belief revision and its relation to updating of logical databases, and explores the relationship between belief revision and nonmonotonic logic.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] This use of abduction is not straightforward, as adding propositional formulae to other propositional formulae can only make inconsistencies worse.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Instead, abduction is done at the level of the ordering of preference of the possible worlds.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Preference models use fuzzy logic or utility models.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In the philosophy of science, abduction has been the key inference method to support scientific realism, and much of the debate about scientific realism is focused on whether abduction is an acceptable method of inference.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In historical linguistics, abduction during language acquisition is often taken to be an essential part of processes of language change such as reanalysis and analogy.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In applied linguistics research, abductive reasoning is starting to be used as an alternative explanation to inductive reasoning, in recognition of anticipated outcomes of qualitative inquiry playing a role in shaping the direction of analysis.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] It is defined as "The use of an unclear premise based on observations, pursuing theories to try to explain it" (Rose et al., 2020, p.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is used as the mechanism for getting from art to agency.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] That is, abduction can explain how works of art inspire a *sensus communis:* the commonly held views shared by members that characterize a given society.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the answer to this conundrum because the tentative nature of the abduction concept (Peirce likened it to guessing) means that not only can it operate outside of any pre-existing framework, but moreover, it can actually intimate the existence of a framework.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] As Gell reasons in his analysis, the physical existence of the artwork prompts the viewer to perform an abduction that imbues the artwork with intentionality.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] A statue of a goddess, for example, in some senses actually becomes the goddess in the mind of the beholder; and represents not only the form of the deity but also her intentions (which are adduced from the feeling of her very presence).
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Therefore, through abduction, Gell claims that art can have the kind of agency that plants the seeds that grow into cultural myths.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] The power of agency is the power to motivate actions and inspire ultimately the shared understanding that characterizes any given society.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In formal methods, logic is used to specify and prove properties of computer programs.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] Abduction has been used in mechanized reasoning tools to increase the level of automation of the proof activity.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] It led to a program-proof startup company, which was acquired by Facebook, and the Infer program analysis tool, which led to thousands of bugs being prevented in industrial codebases.
[src:aesthetics/abductive-reasoning] In addition to inference of function preconditions, abduction has been used to automate inference of invariants for program loops, inference of specifications of unknown code, and in synthesis of the programs themselves.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] "about the dharma") refers to a class of Buddhist texts, the first of which date from the 3rd century BCE.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharma texts contain detailed scholastic presentations of Buddhist doctrine, including doctrines that appear in canonical Buddhist scriptures and commentaries.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] "Abhidharma" also refers to the scholastic method itself, and the knowledge (prajña) that this method is said to study and cultivate.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] There are different types of Abhidharma literature.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The early canonical Abhidharma works, such as the Pali *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*, are not philosophical treatises but mainly summaries and expositions of early Buddhist doctrinal lists with their accompanying explanations.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These texts developed out of early Buddhist lists or matrices (*mātṛkās*) of key teachings.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Later post-canonical Abhidharma works were written as either large treatises (*śāstra*), as commentaries (*aṭṭhakathā*), or as smaller introductory manuals.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] There were numerous schools of Abhidharma in India, such as the Theravada, and the Vaibhāṣika.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They are more developed philosophical works which include many innovations and doctrines not found in the canonical Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharma remains an important field of scholarship among the Theravāda, Mahāyāna, and Vajrayāna schools of Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They held that Abhidharma was taught by the Buddha to his most eminent disciples, and that therefore this justified the inclusion of Abhidharma texts into their scriptural canon.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Collett Cox, Abhidharma started as a systematic elaboration of the teachings of the Buddhist sūtras, but later developed independent doctrines.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Two interpretations of the term "Abhi-dharma" are common.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, the initial meaning of Abhidharma in the earliest texts (such as the *Mahāgosiṅga-sutta* and its parallels) was simply a discussion concerning the Dharma, or talking about the Dharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In this sense, *abhi* has the meaning of "about" or "concerning," and can also be seen in the parallel term *abhivinaya* (which just means discussions about the vinaya).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The other interpretation, where *abhi* is interpreted as meaning "higher" or "superior", and thus *Abhidharma* means "higher teaching", seems to have been a later development.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Some Western scholars have considered the Abhidharma to be the core of what is referred to as "Buddhism and psychology".
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Other scholars on the topic, such as Nyanaponika Thera and Dan Lusthaus, describe Abhidharma as a Buddhist phenomenology while Noa Ronkin and Kenneth Inada equate it with process philosophy.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Bhikkhu Bodhi writes that the system of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* is "simultaneously a philosophy, a psychology and an ethics, all integrated into the framework of a program for liberation." According to L.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Cousins, the Buddhist sūtras deal with sequences and processes, while the Abhidharma texts describe occasions and events.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Modern scholars generally believe that the canonical Abhidharma texts emerged after the time of Gautama Buddha, in around the 3rd century BCE.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Therefore, the canonical Abhidharma works are generally claimed by scholars not to represent the words of the Buddha himself, but those of later Buddhist thinkers.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Peter Skilling describes the Abhidharma literature as "the end-product of several centuries of intellectual endeavor".
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Vinaya accounts on the compilation of the Buddhist Canon following the *parinirvāṇa* of Gautama Buddha (c.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] 5th century BCE) offer various and sometimes conflicting narratives regarding the canonical status of Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, "the Mūlasarvāstivāda Vinaya does not explicitly mention the Abhidharma, although it reports that on this occasion Mahākāśyapa recited the mātṛkā(s)." Analayo thinks that this reflects an early stage, when what later became Abhidharma was called the *mātṛkās*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The term appears in some sūtras, such as the *Mahāgopālaka-sutta* (and its Sanskrit parallel) which says that a learned monk is one who knows the Dharma, Vinaya, and the mātṛkās.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Western scholars of Buddhist studies such as André Migot, Edward J.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Thomas, Erich Frauwallner, Rupert Gethin, and Johannes Bronkhorst have argued that the Abhidharma was based on early and ancient lists of doctrinal terms which are called *mātikās* (Sanskrit: *mātṛkā*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Migot points to the mention of a "*Mātṛkā Piṭaka"* in the *Cullavagga* as the precursor to the canonical *Abhidharma*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Migot argues that this *Mātṛkā Piṭaka*, said to have been recited by Mahākāśyapa at the First Council according to the *Ashokavadana*, likely began as a condensed version of the Buddhist doctrine that was expanded over time.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Thomas and Frauwallner both argue that while the Abhidharma texts of the different schools were compiled separately and have major differences, they are based on an "ancient core" of common material.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Rupert Gethin also writes that the *mātikās* are from an earlier date than the Abhidharma texts themselves.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The extensive use of *mātṛkā* can be found in some early Buddhist texts, including the *Saṅgīti Sutta* and *Dasuttara Sutta* of the Dīgha Nikāya, as well as the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and *Daśottara Sūtra* of the Dīrgha Āgama.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Similar lists of numerically arranged doctrinal terms can be found in AN 10.27 and AN 10.28.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Tse fu Kuan also argues that certain sūtras of the *Aṅguttara Nikāya* (AN 3.25, AN 4.87–90, AN 9.42–51) illustrates an Abhidharma method.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Another text which contains a similar list that acts as a doctrinal summary is the *Madhyama-āgama* ("Discourse on Explaining the Spheres", MĀ 86) which includes a list of thirty one topics to be taught to newly ordained monastics.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The last sutra of the *Madhyama-āgama* (MĀ 222) contains a similar doctrinal summary listing, which combines three lists into one: a list of eight activities, a list of ten mental qualities and practices, and the twelve links of dependent arising.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These two do not have any parallels in Pali.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, another important doctrinal list which appears in the early texts is the "thirty seven qualities that are conducive to awakening" (*bodhipākṣikā dharmāḥ*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This *mātṛkā* appears in various sūtras, like the *Pāsādika-sutta*, the *Sāmagāma-sutta* (and their parallels), and in the *Mahāparinirvāṇa-sūtra*, where it is said to have been taught by the Buddha just before passing away.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Analayo notes that these various lists served a useful purpose in early Buddhism since they served as aids for the memorization and teaching of the Buddhist doctrine.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The use of lists containing doctrinal statements can similarly be seen in Jain literature.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The fact that these lists were seen by the early Buddhists as a way to preserve and memorize the doctrine can be seen in the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and its various parallels, which mention how the Jain community became divided over doctrinal matters after the death of their leader.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The sutta depicts Śāriputra as reciting a list of doctrinal terms and stating that the community will remain "united, unanimous, and in unison we will not dispute" regarding the teaching and also states they will recite together the doctrine.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The close connection between the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and Abhidharma can be seen in the fact that it became the basis for one of the seven canonical Abhidharma texts belonging to the Sarvāstivāda school, the *Saṅgītiparyāya*, which is effectively a commentary on the sūtra.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Frauwallner notes that basic fundamental concepts such as the 12 *āyatanāni,* the 18 *dhatāvah*, and the 5 *skandhāh* often occur as a group in the early Buddhist texts.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] He also points out another such list that occurs in various texts "comprises several groups of elements of import for entanglement in the cycle of existence" and was modeled on the *Oghavagga* of the *Samyuttanikaya*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Another related early method is called the *mātṛkā* ("attribute"), and refers to lists of terms divided by a dyad or triad of attributes.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] For example, terms could be grouped into those things that are *rūpa* (form, physical) or *arūpa* (formless), *saṃskṛtam* (constructed) or *asaṃskṛtam,* and the triad of *kuśalam* (wholesome), *akuśalam* (unwholesome), or *avyākṛtam* (indetermined).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] An early form of this method can be found in the *Dasuttara Sutta*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The explanations of the various elements in these lists also dealt with how these elements were connected (*saṃprayoga*) with each other.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Over time, the need arose for an overarching way to classify all these terms and doctrinal elements, and the first such framework was to subsume or include (*saṃgraha*) all main terms into the schema of the 12 *āyatanāni,* the 18 *dhatāvah*, and the 5 *skandhāh*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Over time, the initial scholastic method of listing and categorizing terms was expanded in order to provide a complete and comprehensive systematization of the Buddhist doctrine.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, these various lists were also not presented alone, but included some kind of commentary and explanation which was also part of the oral tradition.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Sometimes this commentary included quotations from other sutras, and traces of this can be found in the canonical Abhidharma texts.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] As time passed, these commentaries and their accompanying lists became inseparable from each other, and the commentaries gained canonical status.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Therefore, the different Buddhist Abhidharma texts were developed over time as Buddhist monks and philosophers expanded their analytical methods in different ways.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Since this happened in different monastic communities located in different regions, they developed in separate doctrinal directions.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This divergence was perhaps enhanced by the various schisms in the early Buddhist community and also by geographic distance.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Frauwallner, the period of the development of the canonical Abhidharma texts is between 250 and 50 BCE.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] By the time, the different canons began to be written down, and as a result the Abhidharma texts of the early Buddhist schools were substantially different, as can be seen in how different the canonical Abhidharma texts are in the Sarvāstivādin and Theravādin schools.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These differences are much more pronounced than among the other canonical collections (Sūtras, Āgama, and Vinaya).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] As such, the Abhidharma collections of the various Buddhist schools are much more unique to each sect.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The various Abhidharmic traditions grew to have very fundamental philosophical disagreements with each other (such as on the status of the person, or temporal eternalism).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Thus, according to Frauwallner, the different Abhidharma canons contained collections of doctrines which were sometimes unrelated to each other and sometimes contradictory.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These different Abhidharmic theories were (together with differences in Vinaya) some of the various causes for the splits in the monastic Saṃgha, which resulted in the fragmented early Buddhist landscape of the early Buddhist schools.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These various Abhidharma works were not accepted by all Indian Buddhist schools as canonical; for example, the Mahāsāṃghika school seems not to have accepted them as part of their Buddhist canon.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Another school included most of the *Khuddaka Nikāya* within the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] After the closing of the foundational Buddhist canons, Abhidharma texts continued to be composed, but now they were either commentaries on the canonical texts (like the Pāli *Aṭṭhakathās* and the *Mahāvibhāṣa*), or independent treatises (*śāstra*) in their own right.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In these post-canonical texts, further doctrinal developments and innovations can be found.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Some of these texts surpassed the canonical Abhidharma in influence and popularity, becoming the orthodox summas of their particular schools' Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Two exegetical texts, both from the 5th century, stand above the rest as the most influential.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The works of Buddhaghosa (5th century CE), particularly the *Visuddhimagga*, remains the main reference work of the Theravāda school, while the *Abhidharmakośa* (4–5th century CE) of Vasubandhu remains the primary source for Abhidharma studies in both Indo-Tibetan Buddhism and East Asian Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In the modern era, only the Abhidharma texts of the Sarvāstivādins and the Theravādins have survived as complete collections, each consisting of seven books with accompanying commentarial literature.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] A small number of other Abhidharma texts are preserved in the Chinese Canon and also in Sanskrit fragments, such as the *Śāriputra Abhidharma Śāstra* of the Dharmaguptaka school and various texts from the Pudgalavāda tradition.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These different traditions have some similarities, suggesting either interaction between groups or some common ground antedating the separation of the schools.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In the Theravāda tradition it was held that the Abhidhamma was not a later addition, but rather was taught in the fourth week of Gautama Buddha's enlightenment.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada tradition is unique in regarding its Abhidharma as having been taught in its complete form by the Buddha as a single teaching, with the exception of the Kathavatthu, which contains material relating to later disputes and was held to only have been presented as an outline.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to their tradition, devas built a beautiful jeweled residence for the Buddha to the north-east of the Bodhi tree, where he meditated and delivered the Abhidharma teachings to gathered deities in the Trāyastriṃśa heaven, including his deceased mother Māyā.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The tradition holds that the Buddha gave daily summaries of the teachings given in the heavenly realm to the bhikkhu Sariputta, who passed them on.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣika held that the Buddha and his disciples taught the Abhidharma, but that it was scattered throughout the canon.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Only after his death was the Abhidharma compiled systematically by his elder disciples and was recited by Ananda at the first Buddhist council.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika school ('those who rely on the sutras') rejected the status of the Abhidharma as being Buddhavacana (word of the Buddha), they held it was the work of different monks after his death, and that this was the reason different Abhidharma schools varied widely in their doctrines.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] However, this school still studied and debated on Abhidharma concepts and thus did not seek to question the method of the Abhidharma in its entirety.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Indeed, there were numerous Abhidharma texts written from an Abhidharma perspective.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma texts' field of inquiry extends to the entire Buddhadharma, since their goal was to outline, systematize and analyze all of the teachings.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharmic thought also extends beyond the sutras to cover new philosophical and psychological ground which is only implicit in sutras or not present at all.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] There are certain doctrines which were developed or even invented by the Abhidharmikas and these became grounds for the debates among the different early Buddhist schools.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The "base upon which the entire [Abhidhamma] system rests" is the 'dhamma theory' and this theory 'penetrated all the early schools'.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] For the Abhidharmikas, the ultimate components of existence, the elementary constituents of experience were called *dhammas* (Pali: *dhammas*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This concept has been variously translated as "factors" (Collett Cox), "psychic characteristics" (Bronkhorst), "phenomena" (Nyanaponika) and "psycho-physical events" (Ronkin).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The early Buddhist scriptures give various lists of the constituents of the person such as the five skandhas, the six or 18 dhatus, and the twelve sense bases.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In Abhidhamma literature, these lists of dhammas systematically arranged and they were seen as the ultimate entities or momentary events which make up the fabric of people's experience of reality.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The idea was to create an exhaustive list of all possible phenomena that make up the world.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The conventional reality of substantial objects and persons is merely a conceptual construct imputed by the mind on a flux of dhammas.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] However, dhammas are never seen as individually separate entities, but are always dependently conditioned by other dhammas in a stream of momentary constellations of dhammas, constantly coming into being and vanishing, always in flux.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Perception and thinking is then seen as a combination of various dhammas.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Cittas (awareness events) are never experienced on their own, but are always intentional and hence accompanied by various mental factors (cetasikas), in a constantly flowing stream of experience occurrences.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Human experience is thus explained by a series of dynamic processes and their patterns of relationships with each other.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Buddhist Abhidhamma philosophers then sought to explain all experience by creating lists and matrices (matikas) of these dhammas, which varied by school.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This dhamma is unconditioned it neither arises nor ceases due to causal interaction.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivada Abhidharma also used these, along with a fifth category: "factors dissociated from thought" (*cittaviprayuktasaṃskāra*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadas also included three dharmas in the fourth "unconditioned" category instead of just one, the dharma of space and two states of cessation.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma project was thus to provide a completely exhaustive account of every possible type of conscious experience in terms of its constituent factors and their relations.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada tradition holds that there were 82 types of possible dhammas – 82 types of occurrences in the experiential world, while the general Sarvastivada tradition eventually enumerated 75 dharma types.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] For the Abhidharmikas, truth was twofold and there are two ways of looking at reality.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] One way is the way of everyday experience and of normal worldly persons.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This is the category of the nominal and the conceptual (paññatti), and is termed the conventional truth (saṃvṛti-satya).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] However, the way of the Abhidharma, and hence the way of enlightened persons like the Buddha, who have developed the true insight (vipassana), sees reality as the constant stream of collections of dharmas, and this way of seeing the world is ultimate truth (paramārtha-satya).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] As the Indian Buddhist Vasubandhu writes: "Anything the idea of which does not occur upon division or upon mental analysis, such as an object like a pot, that is a 'conceptual fiction'.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The ultimately real is otherwise." For Vasubandhu then, something is not the ultimately real if it 'disappears under analysis', but is merely conventional.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The ultimate goal of the Abhidharma is Nirvana and hence the Abhidharmikas systematized dhammas into those which are skillful (kusala), purify the mind and lead to liberation, and those which are unskillful and do not.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma then has a soteriological purpose, first and foremost and its goal is to support Buddhist practice and meditation.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharmikas often used the term svabhāva (Pali: sabhāva) to explain the causal workings of dharmas.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This term was used in different ways by the different Buddhist schools.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This term does not appear in the sutras.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The examination of these characteristics was held to be extremely important, the Sarvastivada Mahavibhasa states "Abhidharma is [precisely] the analysis of the svalaksana and samanya-laksana of dharmas".
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Peter Harvey, the Theravadin view of dharmas was that "'They are dhammas because they uphold their own nature [sabhaava].
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They are dhammas because they are upheld by conditions or they are upheld according to their own nature' (Asl.39).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Visuddhimagga* of Buddhaghosa, the most influential classical Theravada treatise, states that not-self does not become apparent because it is concealed by "compactness" when one does not give attention to the various elements which make up the person.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadins saw dharmas as the ultimately 'real entities' (sad-dravya), though they also held that dharmas were dependently originated.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] For the Sarvastivadins, a synonym for svabhava is avayaya (a 'part'), the smallest possible unit which cannot be analyzed into smaller parts and hence it is ultimately real as opposed to only conventionally real (such as a chariot or a person).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] However, the Sarvastivadins did not hold that dharmas were completely independent of each other, as the Mahavibhasa states: "conditioned dharmas are weak in their intrinsic nature, they can accomplish their activities only through mutual dependence" and "they have no sovereignty (aisvarya).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Svabhava in the early Abhidhamma texts was then not a term which meant ontological independence, metaphysical essence or underlying substance, but simply referred to their characteristics, which are dependent on other conditions and qualities.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Ronkin: "In the early Sarvāstivāda exegetical texts, then, svabhāva is used as an atemporal, invariable criterion determining what a dharma is, not necessarily that a dharma exists.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrantika school accepted the doctrine of svabhāva as referring to the distinctive or main characteristic of a dharma, but rejected the view that they exist in all three times .
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Buddhist philosopher Dharmakirti uses the concept of svabhāva, though he interprets it as being based on causal powers.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Other early Buddhist schools did not accept the svabhava concept, instead positing a kind of nominalism or conceptualism (*prajñaptivada*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This view was widespread among the Mahasamghika Nikaya.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] One school was even called "Prajñaptivada" because of their denial of the ultimate reality of all dharmas and their view that all dharmas are characterized by *prajñapti* (provisional designation or fictitious construction).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Another school called the Vainasikas also held that all dharmas were without svabhava.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Paramārtha (499–569), another school, the Ekavyavahārikas held "that both the mundane and the supramundane factors [dharmas] are merely nominal (*prajñapti*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They therefore claimed that all factors have no real essence, and that hence the same name applies to all [dharmas]." This helps to explain their name as “Ekavyavahārika” (those who propound the single meaning).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Paramārtha also notes that the Lokottaravāda school held "that the mundane factors have arisen from perversion (viparyāsa) and are only nominal (prajñapti)." However, in contrast to the other schools, they also held that the supramundane dharmas (nirvana etc.) were not nominal but real.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This view that dharmas are empty or void is also found in the *Lokānuvartana-sūtra* (‘The Sutra of Conformity with the World’, Taisho No.807) which survives in Chinese and Tibetan translation, and may have been a scripture of the Purvasailas, which was a sub-school of the Mahasamghika.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Another important project for the Abhidharmikas was to outline a theory of causality, especially of how momentary dharmas relate to each other through causes and conditions.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadin analysis focused on six causes (*hetu*), four conditions (*pratyaya*) and five effects (*phala*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Dhammajoti, for the Sarvastivada school, 'causal efficacy is the central criterion for the reality/existence (astitva) of a dharma' and hence they were also sometimes called the 'Hetuvada' school.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] A dharma is real because it is a cause and it has effects, if it had no causal efficacy, it would not exist.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The last book of the Pali Abhidhamma, the Patthana, sets out the main Theravada theory on conditioned relations and causality.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Patthana is an exhaustive examination of the conditioned nature (Paticcasamupada) of all dhammas.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The introduction begins with a detailed list of 24 specific types of conditioned relationships (paccaya) that may pertain between different factors.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The majority of these conditions have counterparts in the Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Pali Abhidhammatthasangaha reduces them all to four main types.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika school used a theory of 'seeds' (bīja) in the mental continuum to explain causal interaction between past and present dharmas, this theory was later developed by the Yogacara school in their theory of “storehouse consciousness” (ālayavijñāna).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] A prominent argument between the Abhidharmikas was on the Philosophy of time.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivādin tradition held the view (expressed in the Vijñanakaya) that dharmas exist in all three times – past, present, future; hence the name of their school means "theory of all exists".
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika, Vibhajyavāda and Theravada schools argued against this eternalist view in favor of presentism (only the present moment exists).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This argument was so central, that north Indian Buddhist schools were often named according to their philosophical position.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] "Those who hold 'all exists' — the past, the present and the future — belong to the Sarvāstivāda.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Vasubandhu initially wrote in favor of Sarvāstivāda, and later critiqued this position.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣika also held an atomistic conception of time which divided time into discrete indivisible moments (kṣaṇa) and saw all events as lasting only for a minute instant (and yet also existing in all three times).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Theravadins also held a theory of momentariness (Khāṇavāda), but it was less ontological than Sarvāstivāda and more focused on the psychological aspects of time.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada divided every dhamma into three different instants of origination (uppādakkhaṇa), endurance (ṭhitikkhaṇa) and cessation (bhaṅgakkhaṇa).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They also held that only mental events were momentary, material events could endure for longer.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] A key problem which the Abhidharmikas wished to tackle was the question of how rebirth and karma works if there is no self to be reborn apart from the five aggregates.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Patthana includes the earliest Pali canonical reference to an important answer to this question: bhavanga, or 'life-continuum'.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This problem was also taken up by a group of Buddhist schools termed the Pudgalavadins or "Personalists" which included the Vātsīputrīya, the Dharmottarīya, the Bhadrayānīya, the Sammitiya and the Shannagarika.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These schools posited the existence of a 'person' (pudgala) or self, which had a real existence that was not reducible to streams and collections of dharmas.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They also often used other terms to refer to this real 'self', such as 'Atman' and 'Jiva' which are words for the immortal soul in Hinduism and Jainism respectively.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They seemed to have held that the 'self' was part of a fifth category of existence, the “inexpressible”.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This was a radically different view than the not-self view held by the mainstream Buddhist schools and this theory was a major point of controversy and was thoroughly attacked by other Buddhist schools such as the Theravadins, Sarvastivadins and later Mahayanists.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadin Abhidharmikas also developed the novel idea of an intermediate state between death and the next rebirth.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Purvasaila, Sammitiya, Vatsiputriya, and later Mahisasaka schools accepted this view, while the Theravadins, Vibhajyavada, Mahasanghika, and the Sariputrabhidharmasastra of the Dharmaguptakas rejected it.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Some Abhidharmikas such as the Sarvastivadins also defended an atomic theory.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] However unlike the Hindu Vaisheshika school, Abhidharmic atoms (paramannu) are not permanent, but momentary.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Vaibhasika held that an atom is the smallest analyzable unit of matter (rupa), hence it is a 'conceptual atom' (prajnapti-paramanu), though this also corresponds to a real existing thing.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] "An atom (paramänu) is the smallest rüpa.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] It cannot be cut, broken, penetrated; it cannot be taken up, abandoned, ridden on, stepped on, struck or dragged.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] It is neither long nor short, square nor round, regular nor irregular, convex nor concave.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] It has no smaller parts; it cannot be decomposed, cannot be seen, heard, smelled, touched.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* is the third pitaka, or basket, of the Tipitaka (Sanskrit: *Tripiṭaka*), the canon of the Theravāda school.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*, like the rest of the Theravāda *Tipiṭaka*, was orally transmitted until the 1st century BCE.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Due to famines and constant wars, the monks responsible for recording the oral tradition felt that there was a risk of portions of the canon being lost so the Abhidhamma was written down for the first time along with the rest of the Pāli Canon in the first century BCE.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The books of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* were translated into English in the 20th century and published by the Pāli Text Society.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In addition to the canonical Abhidharma, Pali literature includes a variety of Abhidhamma commentaries and introductory manuals written after the compilation of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] These post-canonical texts attempted to expand and further clarify the analysis presented in the Abhidhamma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The most influential of these commentaries are those of Buddhaghosa (c.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] 5th century) a South Indian exegete and philosopher who moved to Sri Lanka and wrote various commentaries and treatises in Pali.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] His *Visuddhimagga* ("Path of Purification") is a comprehensive manual of Buddhist practice that also contains an overview of the Abhidhamma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This text remains one of the most popular Abhidhamma influenced texts in Theravada.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Sri Lankan Theravādins also composed shorter introductory manuals to the Abhidhamma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The most popular and widely used of these remains the *Abhidhammatthasangaha* (*Compendium of the Topics of the Abhidharma*) by Anuruddha (circa 8th to 12th century).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] A further period of medieval Sri Lankan scholarship also produced a series of texts called the *sub-commentaries* (which are commentaries to the commentaries).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Abhidhamma remains a living tradition in Theravāda nations today and modern Abhidhamma works continue to be written in modern languages such as Burmese and Sinhala.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Abhidhamma studies are particularly stressed in Myanmar, where it has been the primary subject of study since around the 17th century.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] One of the most important figures in modern Myanmar Buddhism, Ledi Sayadaw (1846–1923), was well known for his writings on Abhidhamma (especially his commentary on the *Abhidhammatthasangaha,* called the *Paramatthadipanitika*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The most influential Indian Abhidharma tradition was that of the Sarvāstivāda Vaibhāṣika school, which was dominant in North India, especially Kashmir and also in Bactria and Gandhara.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This is the Abhidharma tradition that is studied in East Asian Buddhism and also in Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Like the Theravada Abhidharma, the Sarvāstivāda *Abhidharma Pitaka* also consists of seven texts, but they are quite different works, unlike the Sarvāstivāda Agamas, which are very close, often identical, to the suttas of the Theravada *Sutta Pitaka*.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to Frauwallner however, the two Abhidharma collections share an "ancient core", which is basically an early doctrinal list of dharmas.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The core canonical work of this school, the *Jñānaprasthāna* ('Foundation of Knowledge'), also known as *Aṣṭaskandha* or *Aṣṭagrantha,* was said to be composed by master Kātyāyanīputra.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This became the basis for the *Abhidharma Mahāvibhāṣa Śāstra* ("Great Commentary"), an encyclopedic work which became the central text of the Vaibhāṣika tradition who became the Kasmiri Sarvāstivāda Orthodoxy under the patronage of the Kushan Empire.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Despite numerous variations and doctrinal disagreements within the tradition, most Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣikas were united in their acceptance of the doctrine of "*sarvāstitva*" (all exists), which says that all phenomena in the three times (past, present and future) can be said to exist.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Another defining Vaibhāṣika doctrine was that of simultaneous causation (*sahabhū-hetu*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] In addition to the core Vaibhāṣika Abhidharma literature, a variety of expository texts or treatises were written to serve as overviews and introductions to the Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The oldest one of these was the *Abhidharma-hṛdaya-sastra* (*The Heart of Abhidharma*), by the Tocharian Dharmasresthin, (c.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This text became the model for most of the later treatises.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The most influential of these treatises however, is certainly the *Abhidharmakośabhāsya* (*Treasury of Higher Knowledge*, 5th century), a series of verses and accompanying commentary by Vasubandhu.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] It often critiques Vaibhāṣika views from a Sautrantika perspective.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrantikas were a dissent group within the Sarvāstivāda tradition that rejected many of the core Vaibhāṣika views.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This text remains the main source for Abhidharma in Indo-Tibetan and East Asian Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The most mature and refined form of Vaibhāṣika philosophy can be seen in the work of master Saṃghabhadra (ca fifth century CE), "undoubtedly one of the most brilliant Abhidharma masters in India".
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] His two main works, the **Nyāyānusāra* (*Shun zhengli lun* 順正理論) and the **Abhidharmasamayapradīpikā* (*Apidamo xian zong lun* 阿毘達磨顯宗論), are key sources of late Vaibhāṣika Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Śāriputra Abhidharma Śāstra* (舍利弗阿毘曇論 *Shèlìfú Āpítán Lùn*) (T.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] 1548) is a complete abhidharma text that is thought to come from the Dharmaguptaka sect.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The only complete edition of this text is that in Chinese.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Sanskrit fragments from this text have been found in Bamiyan, Afghanistan, and are now part of the Schøyen Collection (MS 2375/08).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The manuscripts at this find are thought to have been part of a monastery library of the Mahāsāṃghika Lokottaravāda sect.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Several Pudgalavada Abhidharma type texts also survive in Chinese, such as the *Traidharmakasastra* (Taisho no.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] 15c-30a) and the *Sammatiyanikayasastra.* These texts contain traditional Abhidharma type lists and doctrines, but they also expound and defend the Pudgalavada doctrine of the "person" (*pudgala*).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Many Abhidharma texts have been lost—likely more than have survived.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This includes texts brought from India by Xuanzang belonging to a variety of Indian schools that were never translated into Chinese.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Many Abhidharma sastras discovered among the Gandharan Buddhist texts have no parallel in existing Indic languages or Chinese or Tibetan translation, suggesting the former breadth of Abhidharma literature.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] According to some sources, abhidharma was not accepted as canonical by the Mahāsāṃghika school.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The Theravādin *Dīpavaṃsa*, for example, records that the Mahāsāṃghikas had no abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] However, other sources indicate that there were such collections of abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] During the early 5th century, the Chinese pilgrim Faxian is said to have found a Mahāsāṃghika Abhidharma at a monastery in Pāṭaliputra.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] When Xuanzang visited Dhānyakaṭaka, he wrote that the monks of this region were Mahāsāṃghikas, and mentions the Pūrvaśailas specifically.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Near Dhānyakaṭaka, he met two Mahāsāṃghika bhikṣus and studied Mahāsāṃghika abhidharma with them for several months, during which time they also studied various Mahāyāna śāstras together under Xuanzang's direction.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] On the basis of textual evidence as well as inscriptions at Nāgārjunakoṇḍā, Joseph Walser concludes that at least some Mahāsāṃghika sects probably had an abhidharma collection, and that it likely contained five or six books.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Tattvasiddhi Śāstra* ("the treatise that accomplishes reality"; Chinese: 成實論, *Chéngshílun*), is an extant Abhidharma text which was popular in Chinese Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This Abhidharma is now contained in the Chinese Buddhist canon, in sixteen fascicles (Taishō Tripiṭaka 1646).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Its authorship is attributed to Harivarman, a third-century monk from central India.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This work may belong to the Mahāsāṃghika Bahuśrutīya school or to the Sautrāntika school.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Paramārtha cites this Bahuśrutīya abhidharma as containing a combination of Hīnayāna and Mahāyāna doctrines, and Joseph Walser agrees that this assessment is correct.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] Ian Charles Harris also characterizes the text as a synthesis of Hīnayāna and Mahāyāna, and notes that its doctrines are very close to those in Mādhyamaka and Yogācāra works.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Tattvasiddhi Śāstra* maintained great popularity in Chinese Buddhism, and even lead to the formation of its own school of Buddhism in China, the *Chéngshí school* (成實宗), which was founded in 412 CE.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Chéngshí* School taught a progression of twenty-seven stations for cultivating realization, based upon the teachings of this text.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] They took Harivarman as its founder in India, and Kumārajīva as the school's founder in China.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] The *Chéngshí* School is counted among the ten schools of Tang dynasty Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] From China, the *Chéngshí* School was transmitted to Japan in 625 CE, where it was known as *Jōjitsu-shu* (成實宗).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p01] This school is known as one of the six great schools of Japanese Buddhism in the Nara period (710–794 CE).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] Another complete system of Abhidharma thought is elaborated in certain works of the Mahāyāna Yogācāra tradition (which mainly evolved out of the Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma).
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] This Yogācāra Abhidharma can be found in the works of figures like Asanga, Vasubandhu, Sthiramati, Dharmapāla, Śīlabhadra, Xuanzang (Hsüan-tsang), and Vinītadeva.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] Yogācārins developed an Abhidharma literature set within a Mahāyāna framework.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] The *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras and associated literature are influenced by Abhidharma.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] These texts make use of Abhidharma categories (like the dharma theory), and adopt them or critique them in different ways.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] According to Edward Conze, the *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras were meant to be a criticism of the view held by some of the Abhidharmikas which saw dharmas as real.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] Conze also notes that the later *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras have been expanded by the insertion of various doctrinal Abhidharma lists.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] There is also plenty of Abhidharma material (mainly Sarvāstivāda) in the *Dà zhìdù lùn* (*The Treatise on the Great Prajñāpāramitā*; Chinese: 大智度論, *Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa** Taishō Tripiṭaka no.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] The *Dà zhìdù lùn* was translated into Chinese by Kumārajīva (344–413 CE) and his student Sengrui.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] The work claims it is written by Nāgārjuna (c.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] 2nd century), but various scholars such as Étienne Lamotte and Paul Demiéville, have questioned this, holding that the author was instead a Sarvāstivāda monk learned in Abhidharma who became a Mahāyānist and wrote this text.
[src:aesthetics/abhidharma-p02] It is a very influential text in East Asian Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta was born in a Kānyakubja Brāhmin family of scholars and mystics whose ancestors immigrated from Kannauj on invitation by the great king of Kashmir, Lalitaditya Muktapida.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] He studied all the schools of philosophy and art of his time under the guidance of as many as fifteen (or more) teachers and gurus.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] In his long life he completed over 35 works, the largest and most famous of which is *Tantrāloka*, an encyclopedic treatise on all the philosophical and practical aspects of Kaula and Trika (known today as Kashmir Shaivism).
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Another one of his very important contributions was in the field of philosophy of aesthetics with his famous *Abhinavabhāratī* commentary of *Nāṭyaśāstra* of Bharata Muni.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] "Abhinavagupta" was not his real name, rather a title he earned from his Guru, meaning "competence and authoritativeness".
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] In his analysis, Jayaratha (1150–1200 AD) – who was Abhinavagupta's most important commentator – also reveals three more meanings: "being ever vigilant", "being present everywhere" and "protected by praises".
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Raniero Gnoli, the only Sanskrit scholar who completed a translation of Tantrāloka in a European language, mentions that "Abhinava" also means "new", as a reference to the ever-new creative force of his mystical experience.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta's creation is well equilibrated between the branches of the triad (Trika): will (*icchā*), knowledge (*jñāna*), action (*kriyā*); his works also include devotional songs, academical/philosophical works and works describing ritual/yogic practices.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] As an author, he is considered a systematiser of the philosophical thought.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] He reconstructed, rationalised and orchestrated the philosophical knowledge into a more coherent form, assessing all the available sources of his time.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Various contemporary scholars have characterised Abhinavagupta as a "brilliant scholar and saint", "the pinnacle of the development of Kaśmir Śaivism" and "in possession of yogic realization".
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The term by which Abhinavagupta himself defines his origin is "yoginībhū", 'born of a yoginī'.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] In Kashmir Shaivism and especially in Kaula it is considered that a progeny of parents "established in the divine essence of Bhairava", is endowed with exceptional spiritual and intellectual prowess.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Such a child is supposed to be "the depository of knowledge", who "even as a child in the womb, has the form of Shiva", to enumerate but a few of the classical attributes of his kind.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta was born in a Kanyakubja Brahmin family in Kashmir.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] His mother, *Vimalā* (*Vimalakalā*) died when Abhinavagupta was just two years old; as a consequence of losing his mother, to whom he was reportedly very attached, he grew more distant from worldly life and focused all the more on spiritual endeavour.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The father, Narasiṃhgupt, after his wife's death favoured an ascetic lifestyle, while raising his three children.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] He had a cultivated mind and a heart "outstandingly adorned with devotion to Mahesvara (Shiva)" (in Abhinavagupta's own words).
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] He was Abhinavagupta's first teacher, instructing him in grammar, logic and literature.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta had a brother and a sister.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] His brother, Manoratha, was a well-versed devotee of Shiva.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] His sister, Ambā (probable name, according to Navjivan Rastogi), devoted herself to worship after the death of her husband in late life.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] His cousin Karṇa demonstrated even from his youth that he grasped the essence of Śaivism and was detached of the world.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] His wife was presumably Abhinavagupta's older sister Ambā, who looked with reverence upon her illustrious brother.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta also mentions his disciple Rāmadeva as faithfully devoted to scriptural study and serving his master.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Another cousin was Kṣema, possibly the same as Abhinavagupta's illustrious disciple Kṣemarāja.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Mandra, a childhood friend of Karṇa, was their host in a suburban residence; he was not only rich and in possession of a pleasing personality, but also equally learned.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] And last but not least, Vatasikā, Mandra's aunt, who got a special mention from Abhinavagupta for caring for him with exceptional dedication and concern; to express his gratitude, Abhinavagupta declared that Vatasikā deserved the credit for the successful completion of his work.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The emerging picture here is that Abhinavagupta lived in a nurturing and protected environment, where his creative energies got all the support they required.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Everyone around him was filled with spiritual fervor and had taken Abhinavagupta as their spiritual master.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Such a supporting group of family and friends was equally necessary as his personal qualities of genius, to complete a work of the magnitude of Tantrāloka.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] By Abhinavagupta's own account, his most remote known ancestor was called Atrigupta, born in antarved Kānyakubja in Madhyadesha, i.e. the Middle Country.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] From Madhyadeśa he travelled to Kashmir at the request of king Lalitāditya, around year 740 CE.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta is famous for his voracious thirst for knowledge.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] To study he took many teachers (as many as fifteen), both mystical philosophers and scholars.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] He approached Vaiṣṇavas, Buddhists, Śiddhānta Śaivists, and the Trika scholars.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Among the most prominent of his teachers, he enumerates four, two of whom were Vāmanātha, who instructed him in dualistic Śaivism, and Bhūtirāja in the dualist/nondualist school.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Besides being the teacher of the famous Abhinavagupta, Bhūtirāja was also the father of two eminent scholars.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Lakṣmaṇagupta, a direct disciple of Utpaladeva, in the lineage of Trayambaka, was highly respected by Abhinavagupta and taught him all the schools of monistic thought: Krama, Trika, and Pratyabhijña (except Kula). Śambhunātha taught him the fourth school (Ardha-trayambaka).
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] This school is in fact Kaula, and it was emanated from Trayambaka's daughter.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] For Abhinavagupta, Śambhunātha was the most admired guru.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The energy of this initiation is transmitted and sublimated into the heart and finally into consciousness.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Such a method is difficult but very rapid and is reserved for those who shed their mental limitations and are pure.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] It was Śambhunātha who requested he write Tantrāloka.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] As guru, he had a profound influence in the structure of Tantrāloka and in the life of its creator, Abhinavagupta.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] As many as twelve more of his principal teachers are enumerated by name but without details.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] It is believed that Abhinavagupta had more secondary teachers.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Moreover, during his life he had accumulated a large number of texts from which he quoted in his magnum opus, in his desire to create a syncretic, all-inclusive system, where the contrasts of different scriptures could be resolved by integration into a superior perspective.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Such union is essentially non-physical and universal, and thus Abhinavagupta conceived himself as always in communion with Shiva-Shakti.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] In the context of his life and teachings, Abhinavagupta parallels Shiva as both ascetic and enjoyer.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta studied assiduously at least until the age of thirty or thirty-five.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] To accomplish that he travelled, mostly inside Kashmir.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] By his own testimony, he had attained spiritual liberation through his Kaula practice, under the guidance of his most admired master, Śambhunātha.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] He lived in his home (functioning as an ashram) with his family members and disciples, and he did not become a wandering monk, nor did he take on the regular duties of his family, but lived out his life as a writer and a teacher.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta's personality was described as a living realisation of his vision.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] In an epoch pen-painting, Abhinavagupta is depicted seated in Vīrāsana, surrounded by devoted disciples and family, performing a kind of trance-inducing music on a veena while dictating verses of Tantrāloka to one of his attendees--behind him two dūtī (female yogīs) waiting on him.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] They were never to be seen again, supposedly translating together into the spiritual world.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Abhinavagupta's works fall into multiple sections: manuals of religious ritual, devotional songs, philosophical works and philosophy of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Bold type faced titles represent the most important ones.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] His most important work was *Tantrāloka* ("Elucidation of Tantra"), a synthesis of the entire Trika system.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The esoteric chapter 29 on the Kaula ritual was translated in English together with *Jayaratha'*s commentary by John R.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] A complex study on the context, authors, contents and references of *Tantrāloka* was published by Navjivan Rastogi, Prof. of the Lucknow University.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The first complete English translation of *Tantrāloka* was published by the Indologist Mark S.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Dyczkowski in 2023 after 45 years of work.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] The last recognized master of the oral tradition of Kashmir Shaivism, Swami Lakshman Joo, gave a condensed version of the key philosophical chapters of *Tantrāloka* in his book, *Kashmir Shaivism – The Secret Supreme*.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Another important text was the commentary on Parātrīśikā, *Parātrīśikāvivaraṇa*, detailing the signification of the phonematic energies and their two sequential ordering systems, Mātṛkā and Mālinī.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] This was the last major translation project of Jaideva Singh.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Tantrasāra ("Essence of Tantra") is a summarised version, in prose, of *Tantrāloka*, which was once more summarised in *Tantroccaya*, and finally presented in a very short summary form under the name of *Tantravaṭadhānikā* – the "Seed of Tantra".
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] One of the most important works of Abhinavagupta is *Īśvarapratyabhijñā-vimarśini* ("Commentary to the Verses on the Recognition of the Lord") and *Īśvarapratyabhijñā-vivṛti-vimarśini* ("Commentary on the explanation of *Īśvarapratyabhijñā*").
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] This treatise is fundamental in the transmission of the *Pratyabhijña* school (the branch of Kashmir Shaivism based on direct recognition of the Lord) to our days.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Another commentary on a *Pratyabhijña* work – *Śivadṛṣtyā-locana* ("Light on Śivadṛṣṭi") – is now lost.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Another lost commentary is *Padārthapraveśa-nirṇaya-ṭīkā* and *Prakīrṇkavivaraṇa* ("Comment on the Notebook") referring to the third chapter of *Vākyapadīya* of Bhartrihari.
[src:aesthetics/abhinavagupta] Two more philosophical texts of Abhinavagupta are *Kathāmukha-tilaka* ("Ornament of the Face of Discourses") and *Bhedavāda-vidāraṇa* ("Confrontation of the Dualist Thesis").
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] According to Hegel, being is ultimately comprehensible only as an all-inclusive whole (*das Absolute*).
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Hegel asserted that in order for the thinking subject (human reason or consciousness) to be able to know its object (the world) at all, there must be in some sense an identity of thought and being.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Otherwise, the subject would never have access to the object and we would have no certainty about any of our knowledge of the world.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] The absolute idealist position dominated philosophy in nineteenth-century Britain and Germany, while exerting significantly less influence in the United States.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] The absolute idealist position should be distinguished from the subjective idealism of Berkeley, the transcendental idealism of Immanuel Kant, or the post-Kantian **critical idealism** (or post-Kantian transcendental idealism) of J.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] For Hegel, the interaction of opposites generates, in a dialectical fashion, all concepts necessary to comprehend what is.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] For Kant, reason was only for us, and the categories only emerged within the subject.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] However, for Hegel, reason is fully immanent.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Spirit emerges from nature in history and, in art, religion, and philosophy, knows itself in its truth.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Hegel shows that the world is not other than self.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] With the realization that mind and world are, by logical necessity, meaningfully coherent, our access to the world is made secure, a security that was lost in Kant's proclamation that the thing-in-itself was ultimately inaccessible.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] In both Schelling and Hegel's systems (especially the latter), the project aims towards a completion of metaphysics.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] As Redding describes it: "While opinions divide as to how Hegel's approach to logic relates to that of Kant, it is important to grasp that for Hegel logic is not simply a science of the form of our thoughts.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] For Schelling, reason was an organic 'striving' in nature, and this striving was one in which the subject and the object approached an identity.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Hegel's doubts about intellectual intuition's ability to prove or legitimate that the particular is in identity with whole led him to progressively formulate a speculative dialectic in which concepts like *Aufhebung* came to be articulated.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Hegel's innovation in German Idealism was to theorize a historical mode of self-consciousness self-reflection capable of generating a more inclusively holistic understanding of what it ultimately means to be rational in the grand scheme of things.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] By the beginning of the 19th century, German idealist philosophy, particularly that of Kant, Hegel, and Fichte, was being read by British philosophers.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Figures such as Samuel Taylor Coleridge, Thomas Carlyle and J.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Ferrier found in idealism an alternative and a response to the then-dominant empiricist views in Britain.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Early authors such as James Hutchison Stirling not only attempted to introduce German idealist thought to Britain, but sought to present their own version of absolute idealism in an English medium.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Green were of the first generation of British idealists who took the work of Hegel and some of his successors and, from their positions as professors at the universities of Glasgow and Oxford, respectively, influenced generations of students.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Absolute idealism was more fully developed in a second generation by their students, especially F.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Bradley's 1893 *Appearance and Reality* and Bosanquet's two volumes of Gifford lectures, *The Principle of Individuality and Value* (1912) and *The Value and Destiny of the Individual* were the most influential volumes of absolute idealism of the period.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] British absolute idealism had an influence not only within philosophy, but in theology, politics, and social and public policy.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Moreover, many of the students of the idealists, in turn, introduced absolute idealism to Canada, southern Africa, and India.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Neo-idealism in Italy took on different characteristics from its English counterpart.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Among its exponents were Guido De Ruggiero, a supporter of social liberalism, and above all Benedetto Croce, who articulated idealism in a historicist sense, and Giovanni Gentile, who theorized an actual idealism, which he saw embodied in the fascist state.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Gentile made a pivotal distinction to factors concerning Idealism's own criteria for reality, which have stood since Berkeley's adage «*esse est percipi*» by distinguishing between the concrete real «act of thinking», and the abstract «static thought».
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] For him, only in "thinking in action" is dialectical self-consciousness that includes everything.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] So Gentile transfused he whole reality of nature, history and spirit in the pure act of thought.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Every thing exists only in the mental act of thinking it: there are no single empirical entities separated from the trascendental consciousness; even the past lives only in the actual, present moment of memory.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Absolute idealism has greatly altered the philosophical landscape.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] This influence is mostly felt in the strong opposition it engendered.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Both logical positivism and analytic philosophy grew out of a rebellion against Hegelianism prevalent in England during the 19th century.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Continental phenomenology, existentialism, and postmodernism also seek to 'free themselves from Hegel's thought'.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Geoffrey Warnock, writing after the demise of absolute idealism as a philosophical movement in Britain, wrote that the absolute idealists were motivated by emotional concerns, which he says Bradley and McTaggart admitted.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] He also criticized them for vagueness and overreliance on rhetoric as opposed to argument, he added that in the writings of some "solemnity and unclarity seem to rise not seldom to the pitch of actual fraud".
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] Martin Heidegger, one of the leading figures of Continental philosophy in the 20th century, sought to distance himself from Hegel's work.
[src:aesthetics/absolute-idealism] One of Heidegger's philosophical themes in *Being and Time* was "overcoming metaphysics," aiming to distinguish his book from Hegelian tracts.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Western art had been, from the Renaissance up to the middle of the 19th century, underpinned by the logic of perspective and an attempt to reproduce an illusion of visible reality.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] By the end of the 19th century, many artists felt a need to create a new kind of art that would encompass the fundamental changes taking place in technology, science, and philosophy.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The sources from which individual artists drew their theoretical arguments were diverse and reflected the social and intellectual preoccupations in all areas of Western culture at that time.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Abstraction indicates a departure from reality in depiction of imagery in art.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] This departure from accurate representation can be slight, partial, or complete.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Artwork which takes liberties, e.g. altering color or form in ways that are conspicuous, can be said to be partially abstract.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Total abstraction bears no trace of any reference to anything recognizable.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] In geometric abstraction, for instance, one is unlikely to find references to naturalistic entities.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Figurative art and total abstraction are almost mutually exclusive.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] But figurative and representational (or realistic) art often contain partial abstraction.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Both geometric abstraction and lyrical abstraction are often totally abstract.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Among the very numerous art movements that embody partial abstraction would be for instance fauvism in which color is conspicuously and deliberately altered vis-a-vis reality, and cubism, which alters the forms of the real-life entities depicted.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] In 19th century Europe, patronage from the church diminished and private patronage from the public became more capable of providing a livelihood for artists.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Three art movements which contributed to the development of abstract art were Romanticism, Impressionism and Expressionism.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Artistic independence for artists was advanced during the 19th century.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] An objective interest in what is seen can be discerned from the paintings of John Constable, J.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Turner, Camille Corot and from them to the Impressionists who continued the *plein air* painting of the Barbizon school.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Early intimations of a new art had been made by James McNeill Whistler who, in his painting *Nocturne in Black and Gold: The Falling Rocket*, (1872), placed greater emphasis on visual sensation than the depiction of objects.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Even earlier than that, with her "spirit" drawings, Georgiana Houghton's choice to work with abstract shapes correlate with the unnatural nature of her subject, in a time when abstraction was not yet a concept (she organized an exhibit in 1871).
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Expressionist painters explored the bold use of paint surface, drawing distortions and exaggerations, and intense color.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Expressionists produced emotionally charged paintings that were reactions to and perceptions of contemporary experience; and reactions to Impressionism and other more conservative directions of late 19th-century painting.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The Expressionists drastically changed the emphasis on subject matter in favor of the portrayal of psychological states of being.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Although artists like Edvard Munch and James Ensor drew influences principally from the work of the Post-Impressionists they were instrumental to the advent of abstraction in the 20th century.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Paul Cézanne had begun as an Impressionist but his aim – to make a logical construction of reality based on a view from a single point, with modulated color in flat areas – became the basis of a new visual art, later to be developed into Cubism.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Additionally in the late 19th century in Eastern Europe mysticism and early modernist religious philosophy as expressed by theosophist Mme.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Blavatsky had a profound impact on pioneer geometric artists like Hilma af Klint and Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The mystical teaching of Georges Gurdjieff and P.D.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Ouspensky also had an important influence on the early formations of the geometric abstract styles of Piet Mondrian and his colleagues in the early 20th century.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The spiritualism also inspired the abstract art of Kasimir Malevich and František Kupka.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The raw language of color as developed by the Fauves directly influenced another pioneer of abstraction, Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Cubism, based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to cube, sphere and cone became, along with Fauvism, the art movement that directly opened the door to abstraction in the early 20th century.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] During the 1912 Salon de la Section d'Or, where František Kupka exhibited his abstract painting *Amorpha, Fugue en deux couleurs* (*Fugue in Two Colors*) (1912), the poet Guillaume Apollinaire named the work of several artists including Robert Delaunay, *Orphism*.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Since the turn of the century, cultural connections between artists of the major European cities had become extremely active as they strove to create an art form equal to the high aspirations of modernism.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Ideas were able to cross-fertilize by means of artist's books, exhibitions and manifestos so that many sources were open to experimentation and discussion, and formed a basis for a diversity of modes of abstraction.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] During the Spring David Burliuk gave two lectures on cubism and planned a polemical publication, which the Knave of Diamonds was to finance.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] He went abroad in May and came back determined to rival the almanac *Der Blaue Reiter* which had emerged from the printers while he was in Germany".
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] From 1909 to 1913 many experimental works in the search for this 'pure art' had been created by a number of artists: Francis Picabia painted *Caoutchouc*, c.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] With his expressive use of color and his free and imaginative drawing, Henri Matisse comes very close to pure abstraction in *French Window at Collioure* (1914), *View of Notre-Dame* (1914), and *The Yellow Curtain* from 1915.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] And the search continued: The Rayist (Luchizm) drawings of Natalia Goncharova and Mikhail Larionov, used lines like rays of light to make a construction.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Kasimir Malevich completed his first entirely abstract work, the Suprematist, *Black Square*, in 1915.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Another of the Suprematist group' Liubov Popova, created the Architectonic Constructions and Spatial Force Constructions between 1916 and 1921.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Piet Mondrian was evolving his abstract language, of horizontal and vertical lines with rectangles of color, between 1915 and 1919, Neo-Plasticism was the aesthetic which Mondrian, Theo van Doesburg and other in the group De Stijl intended to reshape the environment of the future.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Many of the abstract artists in Russia became Constructivists believing that art was no longer something remote, but life itself.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The artist must become a technician, learning to use the tools and materials of modern production.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] *Art into life!* was Vladimir Tatlin's slogan, and that of all the future Constructivists.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Varvara Stepanova and Alexandre Exter and others abandoned easel painting and diverted their energies to theatre design and graphic works.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] On the other side stood Kazimir Malevich, Anton Pevsner and Naum Gabo.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] They argued that art was essentially a spiritual activity; to create the individual's place in the world, not to organize life in a practical, materialistic sense.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] During that time, representatives of the Russian avant-garde collaborated with other Eastern European Constructivist artists, including Władysław Strzemiński, Katarzyna Kobro, and Henryk Stażewski.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Many of those who were hostile to the materialist production idea of art left Russia.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Anton Pevsner went to France, Gabo went first to Berlin, then to England and finally to America.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Kandinsky studied in Moscow then left for the Bauhaus.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] By the mid-1920s the revolutionary period (1917 to 1921) when artists had been free to experiment was over; and by the 1930s only socialist realism was allowed.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] As visual art becomes more abstract, it develops some characteristics of music: an art form which uses the abstract elements of sound and divisions of time.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Wassily Kandinsky, himself an amateur musician, was inspired by the possibility of marks and associative color *resounding in the soul.* The idea had been put forward by Charles Baudelaire, that all our senses respond to various stimuli but the senses are connected at a deeper aesthetic level.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Closely related to this, is the idea that art has *The spiritual dimension* and can transcend 'every-day' experience, reaching a spiritual plane.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The Theosophical Society popularized the ancient wisdom of the sacred books of India and China in the early years of the century.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] It was in this context that Piet Mondrian, Wassily Kandinsky, Hilma af Klint and other artists working towards an 'objectless state' became interested in the occult as a way of creating an 'inner' object.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The universal and timeless shapes found in geometry: the circle, square and triangle become the spatial elements in abstract art; they are, like color, fundamental systems underlying visible reality.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The Bauhaus at Weimar, Germany was founded in 1919 by Walter Gropius.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The philosophy underlying the teaching program was unity of all the visual and plastic arts from architecture and painting to weaving and stained glass.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] This philosophy had grown from the ideas of the Arts and Crafts movement in England and the Deutscher Werkbund.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Among the teachers were Paul Klee, Wassily Kandinsky, Johannes Itten, Josef Albers, Anni Albers, and László Moholy-Nagy.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] In 1925 the school was moved to Dessau and, as the Nazi party gained control in 1932, The Bauhaus was closed.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] In 1937 an exhibition of degenerate art, 'Entartete Kunst' contained all types of avant-garde art disapproved of by the Nazi party.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Then the exodus began: not just from the Bauhaus but from Europe in general; to Paris, London and America.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Paul Klee went to Switzerland but many of the artists at the Bauhaus went to America.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] During the 1930s Paris became the host to artists from Russia, Germany, the Netherlands and other European countries affected by the rise of totalitarianism.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Sophie Tauber and Jean Arp collaborated on paintings and sculpture using organic/geometric forms.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The Polish Katarzyna Kobro applied mathematically based ideas to sculpture.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The many types of abstraction now in close proximity led to attempts by artists to analyse the various conceptual and aesthetic groupings.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] An exhibition by forty-six members of the Cercle et Carré group organized by Joaquín Torres-García assisted by Michel Seuphor contained work by the Neo-Plasticists as well as abstractionists as varied as Kandinsky, Anton Pevsner and Kurt Schwitters.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Criticized by Theo van Doesburg to be too indefinite a collection he published the journal *Art Concret* setting out a manifesto defining an abstract art in which the line, color and surface only are the concrete reality.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Abstraction-Création founded in 1931 as a more open group, provided a point of reference for abstract artists, as the political situation worsened in 1935, and artists again regrouped, many in London.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The first exhibition of British abstract art was held in England in 1935.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The following year the more international *Abstract and Concrete* exhibition was organized by Nicolete Gray including work by Piet Mondrian, Joan Miró, Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Hepworth, Nicholson and Gabo moved to the St.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Ives in Cornwall to continue their constructivist work.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] During the Nazi rise to power in the 1930s many artists fled Europe to the United States.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The rich cultural influences brought by the European artists were distilled and built upon by local New York painters.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The climate of freedom in New York allowed all of these influences to flourish.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The art galleries that primarily had focused on European art began to notice the local art community and the work of younger American artists who had begun to mature.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Certain artists at this time became distinctly abstract in their mature work.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] During this period Piet Mondrian's painting *Composition No.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] 10*, 1939–1942, characterized by primary colors, white ground and black grid lines clearly defined his radical but classical approach to the rectangle and abstract art in general.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Some artists of the period defied categorization, such as Georgia O'Keeffe who, while a modernist abstractionist, was a pure maverick in that she painted highly abstract forms while not joining any specific group of the period.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Eventually American artists who were working in a great diversity of styles began to coalesce into cohesive stylistic groups.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The best-known group of American artists became known as the Abstract expressionists and the New York School.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] In New York City there was an atmosphere which encouraged discussion and there was a new opportunity for learning and growing.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Graham and Hans Hofmann became important bridge figures between the newly arrived European Modernists and the younger American artists coming of age.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Mark Rothko, born in Russia, began with strongly surrealist imagery which later dissolved into his powerful color compositions of the early 1950s.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The expressionistic gesture and the act of painting itself, became of primary importance to Jackson Pollock, Robert Motherwell, and Franz Kline.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] While during the 1940s Arshile Gorky's and Willem de Kooning's figurative work evolved into abstraction by the end of the decade.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] New York City became the center, and artists worldwide gravitated towards it; from other places in America as well.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Digital art, hard-edge painting, geometric abstraction, minimalism, lyrical abstraction, op art, abstract expressionism, color field painting, monochrome painting, assemblage, neo-Dada, shaped canvas painting, are a few directions relating to abstraction in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] In the United States, *Art as Object* as seen in the Minimalist sculpture of Donald Judd and the paintings of Frank Stella are seen today as newer permutations.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Other examples include Lyrical Abstraction and the sensuous use of color seen in the work of painters as diverse as Robert Motherwell, Patrick Heron, Kenneth Noland, Sam Francis, Cy Twombly, Richard Diebenkorn, Helen Frankenthaler, Joan Mitchell, and Veronica Ruiz de Velasco.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] One socio-historical explanation that has been offered for the growing prevalence of the abstract in modern art—an explanation linked to the name of Theodor W.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Adorno—is that such abstraction is a response to (and a reflection of) the growing abstraction of social relations in industrial society.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] Frederic Jameson similarly sees modernist abstraction as a function of the abstract power of money, equating all things equally as exchange-values.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] The social content of abstract art is then precisely the abstract nature of social existence—legal formalities, bureaucratic impersonalization, information/power—in the world of late modernity.
[src:aesthetics/abstract-art] By contrast, Post-Jungians would see the quantum theories with their disintegration of conventional ideas of form and matter as underlying the divorce of the concrete and the abstract in modern art.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Greek philosophical skepticism, as a distinct philosophical movement, began with Pyrrho of Elis (c.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] 270 BCE), with antecedents in Xenophanes and Democritus.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] His followers, the Pyrrhonists, pointed out the problem of the criterion: that our theories and our sense impressions are unable to accurately distinguish truth from falsehood; therefore we must suspend judgment (*epoche*).
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] They were consistent enough to extend their doubt even to their own principle of doubt, making their skepticism universal, thus escaping reproach for basing it upon a fresh dogmatism.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Mental imperturbability (*ataraxia*) was the result to be attained by cultivating such a frame of mind.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Around 266 BCE, Arcesilaus became head of the Platonic Academy.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] He adopted skepticism as a central tenet of Platonism, making Platonism nearly the same as Pyrrhonism.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] After Arcesilaus, the Academics diverged from Pyrrhonism.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] This skeptical period of ancient Platonism, from Arcesilaus to Philo of Larissa, became known as the new Academy, although some ancient authors added further subdivisions, such as a middle Academy.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Following the death of the Pyrrhonist Timon of Phlius, the Platonic Academy became the primary advocate of skepticism until the mid-first century BCE.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] The Academics did not doubt the existence of truth; they just doubted that humans had the capacities for obtaining it.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] They based this position on Plato's *Phaedo*, in which Socrates discusses how knowledge is not accessible to mortals.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] While the objective of the Pyrrhonists was the attainment of ataraxia, after Arcesilaus the Academics did not hold up ataraxia as the central objective.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] The Academics focused on criticizing the dogmas of other schools of philosophy, in particular of the dogmatism of the Stoics.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] They acknowledged some vestiges of a moral law within, at best merely a plausible guide, the possession of which, however, formed the real distinction between the sage and the fool.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Slight as the difference may appear between the positions of the Academics and the Pyrrhonists, a comparison of their lives leads to the conclusion that a practical philosophical moderation was the characteristic of the Academics whereas the objectives of the Pyrrhonists were more psychological.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Up to Arcesilaus, the Platonic Academy accepted the principle of finding a general unity in all things, by the aid of which a principle of certainty might be found.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] The doctrines of Arcesilaus, which must be gathered from the writings of others, represent an attack on the Stoic *phantasia kataleptike* (criterion) and are based on the skepticism which was latent in the later writings of Plato.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Arcesilaus held that strength of intellectual conviction cannot be regarded as valid, inasmuch as it is characteristic equally of contradictory convictions.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] The uncertainty of sense data applies equally to the conclusions of reason, and therefore man must be content with probability which is sufficient as a practical guide.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] "We know nothing, not even our ignorance"; therefore the wise man will be content with an agnostic attitude.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] The next stage in Academic skepticism was the moderate skepticism of Carneades, which he said owed its existence to his opposition to Chrysippus.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] All our sensations are relative, and acquaint us, not with things as they are, but only with the impressions that things produce upon us.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Experience, he said, clearly shows that there is no true impression.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] There is no notion that may not deceive us; it is impossible to distinguish between false and true impressions; therefore the Stoic *phantasia kataleptike* must be given up.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] There is no phantasia kataleptike ("criterion") of truth.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Carneades also assailed Stoic theology and physics.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] In answer to the doctrine of final cause, of design in nature, he pointed to those things which cause destruction and danger to man, to the evil committed by men endowed with reason, to the miserable condition of humanity, and to the misfortunes that assail the good man.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] There is, he concluded, no evidence for the doctrine of a divine superintending providence.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Even if there were orderly connexion of parts in the universe, this may have resulted quite naturally.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] No proof can be advanced to show that this world is anything but the product of natural forces.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Knowledge being impossible, a wise man should practice *epoche* (suspension of judgment).
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] He will not even be sure that he can be sure of nothing.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] He saved himself, however, from absolute skepticism by the doctrine of plausibility, which may serve as a practical guide in life.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Ideas or notions are never true, but only plausible; nevertheless, there are degrees of plausibility, and hence degrees of belief, leading to action.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] According to Carneades, an impression may be plausible in itself; plausible and uncontradicted (not distracted by synchronous sensations, but shown to be in harmony with them) when compared with others; plausible, uncontradicted, and thoroughly investigated and confirmed.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] In the first degree there is a strong persuasion of the propriety of the impression made; the second and third degrees are produced by comparisons of the impression with others associated with it, and an analysis of itself.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Carneades left no written works; his opinions seem to have been systematized by his pupil Clitomachus, whose works, which included one "on suspension of judgment", were made use of by Cicero.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] In Philo of Larissa, we find a tendency not only to reconcile the internal divergences of the Academy itself, but also to connect it with parallel systems of thought.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] In general, his philosophy was a reaction against the skeptic or agnostic position of the middle and new Academy in favor of the dogmatism of Plato.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] Philo of Larissa endeavored to show that Carneades was not opposed to Plato, and further that the apparent antagonism between Platonism and Stoicism was because they were arguing from different points of view.
[src:aesthetics/academic-skepticism] From this syncretism emerged the eclectic middle Platonism of Antiochus of Ascalon, the last product of Academic development.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties are features that influence the appeal of objects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They include aesthetic values, which express positive or negative qualities, such as the contrast between beauty and ugliness.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers debate whether aesthetic properties have objective existence or depend on the subjective experiences of observers.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to a common view, aesthetic experiences are associated with disinterested pleasure detached from practical concerns.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Taste is a subjective sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, and differences in taste can lead to disagreements about aesthetic judgments.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans, encompassing diverse forms such as painting, music, dance, architecture, and literature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some definitions focus on their intrinsic aesthetic qualities; others understand art as a socially constructed category.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Art interpretation and criticism seek to identify the meanings of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Discussions focus on elements such as what an artwork represents, which emotions it expresses, and what the author's underlying intent was.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Many fields of study investigate aesthetic phenomena, examining their roles in ethics, religion, and everyday life, as well as the psychological processes involved in aesthetic experiences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Comparative aesthetics analyzes the similarities and differences between traditions such as Western, Indian, Chinese, Islamic, and African aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic thought has its roots in antiquity but only emerged as a distinct field of inquiry in the 18th century when philosophers systematically engaged with the subject.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetics, sometimes spelled *esthetics*, is the systematic study of beauty, art, and taste.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] As a branch of philosophy, it examines which types of aesthetic phenomena there are, how people experience them, and how objects evoke them.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This field also investigates the nature of aesthetic judgments, the meaning of artworks, and the problem of art criticism.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Key questions in aesthetics include "What is art?", "Can aesthetic judgments be objective?", and "How is aesthetic value related to other values?".
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One characterization distinguishes between three main approaches to aesthetics: the study of aesthetic concepts and judgments, the study of aesthetic experiences and other mental responses, and the study of the nature and features of aesthetic objects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] In a slightly different sense, the term *aesthetics* can also refer to particular theories of beauty or to beautiful appearances.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetics is closely related to the philosophy of art, and the two terms are often used interchangeably since both involve the philosophical study of aesthetic phenomena.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One difference is that the philosophy of art focuses on art, whereas the scope of aesthetics also includes other domains, such as beauty in nature and everyday life.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Accordingly, one outlook argues that the philosophy of art is a subfield of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The precise relation between the two fields is disputed, and another characterization holds that the philosophy of art is the broader discipline.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This view asserts that aesthetics mainly addresses aesthetic properties, while the philosophy of art also investigates non-aesthetic features of artworks, belonging to fields such as metaphysics, epistemology, philosophy of language, and ethics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Even though the philosophical study of aesthetic problems originated in antiquity, it was not until the 18th century that aesthetics emerged as a distinct branch of philosophy when philosophers engaged in systematic inquiry into its principles.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The Latin term *aesthetica* was coined by the philosopher Alexander Baumgarten in 1735, initially defined as the study of sensibility or sensations of beautiful objects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The term comes from the ancient Greek words *aisthetikos*, meaning 'perceptible things', *aisthesthai*, meaning 'perceive, see', and *aisthesis*, meaning 'sensation, perception'.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The earliest known use in the English language appeared in a translation by W.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers rely on several basic concepts in their inquiry.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They examine aesthetic objects and the properties or features responsible for their appeal, such as beauty.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Researchers study the experience and pleasure these objects evoke, the judgments about them, and taste as an underlying sensitivity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] However, this field comes with theoretical difficulties caused by disagreements about the definitions of and relations between these concepts.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Similarly, the exact boundaries of the domain of aesthetics as a whole are disputed—it is controversial whether there is a group of essential features shared by all aesthetic phenomena or whether they are more loosely related through family resemblances.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties are features of an object that shape its appeal or factors that influence aesthetic evaluations.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For instance, when an art critic describes an artwork as *great*, *vivid*, or *amusing*, they express aesthetic properties of this artwork.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some aesthetic properties focus on aesthetic value in general, like *beautiful* and *ugly*; others center on more specific forms of value, such as *graceful* and *elegant*.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties can also refer to perceptual qualities of objects like *balanced* and *vivid*, to representational aspects like *realistic* and *distorted*, or to emotional responses such as *joyful* and *angry*.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The precise distinction between aesthetic and non-aesthetic properties is disputed.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to one proposal, aesthetic properties require a specific aesthetic sensitivity in addition to the sensory perception of non-aesthetic properties, going beyond simple colors, shapes, and sounds.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties are associated with evaluations, but not all are intrinsically good or bad.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, being a realistic representation may be aesthetically good in some artistic contexts and bad in others.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The school of realism argues that aesthetic properties are objective, mind-independent features of reality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A related proposal asserts that they are emergent properties dependent on non-aesthetic properties.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to this view, the beauty of a painting may emerge from the right combination of colors and shapes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A different position holds that aesthetic properties are response-dependent, for example, that features of objects only qualify as aesthetic properties if they evoke aesthetic experiences in observers.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The terms "aesthetic property" and "aesthetic quality" are often used interchangeably.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some philosophers distinguish the two, associating aesthetic properties with objective features and aesthetic qualities with subjective experiences and emotional responses.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An aesthetic object is an object with aesthetic properties.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One interpretation suggests that aesthetic objects are material entities that evoke aesthetic experiences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to this view, if a person admires an oil painting, then the physical canvas and paint make up the aesthetic object.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another interpretation, associated with the school of phenomenology, argues that aesthetic objects are not material but intentional objects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Intentional objects are part of the content of experiences, and their existence depends on the perceiver.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An intentional object may accurately reflect a material object, as in the case of veridical perceptions, but can also fail to do so, which happens during perceptual illusions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The phenomenological perspective focuses on the intentional object given in experience rather than the material object considered independently of the perceiver.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic values are a special type of aesthetic property.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They express the sensory appeal of an object as a qualitative measure of its aesthetic merit, encompassing both positive and negative evaluations.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic values contrast with values in other domains, such as moral, epistemic, religious, and economic values.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The aesthetic value of beauty is often singled out as a central topic of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It is a key aspect of human experience, influencing both personal decisions and cultural developments.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Often-cited examples of beautiful objects include landscapes, sunsets, humans, and artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] As a positive value, beauty contrasts with ugliness as its negative counterpart.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Beauty is typically understood as a quality of objects that involves balance or harmony and evokes admiration or pleasure when perceived, but its precise definition is debated.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some theories understand beauty as an objective feature of external objects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Others emphasize its subjective nature, linking it to personal experience and perception.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They argue that "beauty is in the eye of the beholder" rather than in the perceived object.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another central debate concerns the features that all beautiful objects have in common.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The so-called *classical conception of beauty* is rooted in classical antiquity and the Italian Renaissance.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Focusing on objective features, it asserts that beauty is a harmonious arrangement of parts into a coherent whole.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic hedonism, by contrast, is a subjective theory holding that a thing is beautiful if it acts as a source of aesthetic pleasure.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Other conceptions define beautiful objects in terms of intrinsic value, the manifestation of ideal forms, or as what evokes love and passion.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] In pre-modern philosophy, beauty was often treated as the only aesthetic value.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This outlook holds that beauty encompasses all that is aesthetically commendable and serves as a unifying concept of the whole domain of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] As discussions of aesthetic phenomena expanded, other aesthetic values were proposed.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, the sublime is another value of things that inspire feelings of awe and fear.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Further suggested values include charm, elegance, harmony, and grace.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An aesthetic experience is an appreciation of beauty or an awareness of other aesthetic features.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] In its most typical form, it is a sensory perception of a natural object or an artwork.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It can also take other forms, such as aesthetic imagination of fictional objects described in literature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Internalist theories, like Monroe Beardsley's view, explain aesthetic experience from a first-person perspective, focusing on aspects internal to the experience, such as focus and intensity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] By contrast, externalist theories, such as George Dickie's position, argue that the key element of aesthetic experiences comes from the perceived external objects and their aesthetic properties.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Several features are associated with aesthetic experiences, but it is controversial whether any of them are essential.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic experiences usually appreciate an object for its own sake because of its sensory properties, resulting in aesthetic pleasure from a positive evaluation of the object.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This pleasure is typically said to be detached from practical concerns and can involve selfless absorption, allowing imaginative freedom or free play of mental faculties in addition to sensory perception.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some theorists associate this free play with an absence of conceptual activity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic experiences may also be normative, meaning that certain responses are appropriate, like the positive appreciation of beauty, but others are not, such as the positive appreciation of ugliness.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A central aspect of aesthetic experience is the aesthetic attitude—a special way of observing or engaging with art and nature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This attitude involves a form of pure appreciation of perceptual qualities detached from personal desires and practical concerns.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It is disinterested in this sense by engaging with an object for its own sake without ulterior motives or practical consequences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, the experience of a violent storm through the aesthetic attitude may focus on its intricate patterns of lightning and thunder rather than preparing for its immediate dangers.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One characterization understands the aesthetic attitude as a natural form of apprehension that occurs on its own in certain situations.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another outlook holds that the aesthetic attitude is a voluntary stance people can choose to adopt toward any object.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] There is debate about the extent and type of emotional engagement a disinterested stance requires, for instance, whether fear during a horror movie can be disinterested.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The aesthetic attitude is sometimes contrasted with other attitudes, such as the practical attitude, which is interested in usefulness and seeks to utilize or manipulate objects to achieve specific goals.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Similarly, it differs from the scientific attitude, which aims to explain phenomena and acquire factual knowledge about the world.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some philosophers, such as Arthur Schopenhauer and Martin Heidegger, suggest that the aesthetic attitude can reveal aspects of reality obscured in other attitudes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic experience is further associated with aesthetic pleasure—a form of enjoyment in response to natural and artistic beauty.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It is typically characterized as disinterested pleasure.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It contrasts with interested pleasure that arises from the satisfaction of desires, such as the joy of achieving a personal goal or indulging in a particular type of food one craves.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another difference is that aesthetic pleasure does not depend on the existence of the enjoyed object, like enjoying the beauty of a sunset in a dream.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The joy in achieving a personal goal, by contrast, would be frustrated if one discovered that the achievement was merely a dream.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers like Immanuel Kant argue that aesthetic pleasure is preconceptual, meaning that it arises from a free interplay between imagination and understanding rather than from cognitive judgments or conceptual analysis.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One view distinguishes refined from unrefined aesthetic pleasures based on whether the pleasure is evoked by a cultivated taste or an immediate, instinctual response.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic pleasure is central to the characterization of many aesthetic phenomena that are said to involve or evoke such pleasure.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] However, the view that aesthetic pleasure is the defining characteristic of the entire aesthetic domain is controversial.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It faces challenges in explaining phenomena such as the sublime, drama, tragedy, and forms of modern art, which may evoke diverse emotions not primarily linked to pleasure.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic judgments are assessments of the aesthetic features and values of objects, expressed in statements like "this music is beautiful".
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They can apply both to natural objects and artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic judgments also include assessments about how or why an object has aesthetic value without explicitly determining its overall aesthetic worth, as in the statement "this music is balanced".
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Many debates in aesthetics concern the nature of aesthetic judgments, in particular, whether they can be as objective and universal as empirical judgments made by natural scientists.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Subjectivists argue that aesthetic judgments express personal feelings and dislikes without universal validity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This view is contested by objectivists, who hold that aesthetic judgments describe objective features that are independent of the particular preferences of the judging individual.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Intermediate views suggest that the standards of aesthetic judgment are grounded in stable shared dispositions rather than variable individual preferences, resulting in a form of subjective universality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This position is reflected in Kant's view, which identifies four core features of aesthetic judgments: they are subjective, universal, disinterested, and involve an interplay of sense, imagination, and understanding.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers such as Francis Hutcheson and David Hume argue that there are general aesthetic principles or universal criteria that are applied when making aesthetic judgments.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Particularists, by contrast, assert that the unique nature of each aesthetic object requires a case-by-case evaluation that cannot be fully subsumed under general principles.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A related debate between rationalism and the immediacy thesis concerns whether aesthetic judgments are mediated through concept application and reasoning or emerge directly from sensory intuition.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic judgments rely on taste, which is a sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, a capacity to feel aesthetic pleasure, or an ability to discern beauty and other aesthetic qualities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Taste is a type of preference expressed in immediate reactions and is sometimes understood as an inner sense or cognitive faculty.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Differences in taste are often used to explain why people disagree about aesthetic judgments and why the judgments of some people, such as art critics with extensive experience and a refined sense, carry more weight than those of casual observers.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Taste varies both among cultures and among individuals within a culture.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] There are also some cross-cultural agreements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Several philosophers argue that taste can be learned to some extent and that the judgments of experienced observers follow similar standards, suggesting the existence of social norms of right and wrong aesthetic assessments.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The term "aesthetic universal" refers to aspects of taste and other aesthetic phenomena that are shared across different cultures and societies, indicating common features of human nature underlying aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Suggested general tendencies include the dispositions to engage in artistic expressions or to derive aesthetic pleasure from appreciating these expressions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The existence of more specific shared tendencies is debated.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An example is the idea that humans generally find savanna-like landscapes with open grassy plains and scattered trees pleasing.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Art is a central topic of aesthetics and the main subject of the philosophy of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It encompasses diverse forms, including painting, sculpture, music, dance, literature, and theater.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This field covers both artworks and the skills or activities involved in their creation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They differ in this respect from naturally occurring aesthetic objects, like landscapes and sunsets.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A central debate in the philosophy of art concerns the definition of art or how to distinguish it from non-art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] There are many theories, each offering a unique perspective on the nature of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Essentialist approaches argue that there is an essence or a set of inherent features shared by all artworks and only by them.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They often define artworks in terms of other aesthetic concepts, such as *representation*, *beauty*, or *aesthetic experience*.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An early object-centered approach, first proposed by Plato, characterizes artworks as representations that seek to reflect or imitate certain aspects of reality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another definition suggests that artworks are objects designed to evoke aesthetic experiences or pleasure.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A related approach proposes that all artworks have certain aesthetic properties in common, such as beauty.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic formalism argues that specific formal features, such as a "significant form", are the hallmark of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Artist-centered approaches see artistic activity as the essential aspect of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One conception understands artworks as special vehicles through which artists express emotions and other mental states.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Conventionalist definitions view art as a socially constructed category.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This means that it does not primarily depend on the inherent properties of objects, for example, what they represent or what forms they have.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Instead, art is defined by social and cultural agreements, which are subject to change.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A key motivation for this approach has been the emergence of modern art, which has challenged many earlier conceptions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Conventionalist definitions can explain, for instance, that even mundane ready-made objects like a urinal are considered art if conventions say so.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Institutional theories argue that the conventions are set by social institutions of the art world.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Because of this social dependence, an object considered art in one society may not be art in another society.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Historical theories, another form of conventionalism, assert that the category of art depends on established traditions and historical contexts.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They claim that an object becomes part of this category if it stands in the right relation to these traditions, for example, by being created in an artistic context and resembling other recognized artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] There are also hybrid theories that combine elements from other theories.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For instance, one approach holds that an object is an artwork if it either meets certain aesthetic standards or is conventionally regarded as art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The diversity of proposed definitions and the difficulties in reconciling them have led some philosophers to argue against the existence of precise criteria.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some conclude that a definition is strictly impossible.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Others provide vague characterizations, suggesting that the domain of art is characterized by overlapping similarities, known as family resemblance.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The ontology of art seeks to discern the fundamental categories of being to which all artworks belong.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One approach argues that artworks are universals—general or repeatable entities that can have several instances at the same time.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, a novel can have many copies, a film can have many screenings, and a photo can have many prints.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One version of this view distinguishes artworks as types from their instances, which are considered tokens of this type.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A different outlook rejects the idea that artworks are universals, arguing instead that they are particulars or unique concrete entities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For them, if there are several instances, then the artwork is the collection or sum of all instances.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to this view, Alfred Stieglitz's photograph *The Steerage* is not a type underlying its prints but rather the collection or sum of all prints together.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A similar discussion addresses whether artworks are material objects, which exist independent of observers, or intentional objects, which exist in the experience of observers.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Pluralists argue that different types of artworks belong to distinct ontological categories.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Contextualists accept this view and further propose that the ontological category depends on the context of discussion.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Deflationism is skeptical about the fundamental existence of artworks in any form.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It acknowledges that the term *art* may be practically useful in everyday language but rejects that it refers to any fundamental entities of reality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some distinctions focus on the medium used to express artistic ideas.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, paintings typically use paint, such as oil or acrylic paint, which is distributed on a surface, whereas dance involves bodily movements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Similarly, music is performed using instruments and voice to produce sounds, and literature relies on language.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Hybrid forms like opera and film combine several of these elements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another distinction is between performance works and object works.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Performance works, like a song performed on stage, are dynamically enacted in time, whereas object works, like a painting, have a more static nature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Artworks can also be classified by art historic style, such as impressionism and surrealism, and by their intended purpose, like political and religious art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The meaning of an artwork is what is involved in understanding it or comprehending what it communicates, encompassing factors such as representation and expression.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Certain aspects of meaning may be directly accessible; others require in-depth interpretation, for example, to grasp symbolic or metaphorical elements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Understanding influences aesthetic experience, and for certain artworks, a comprehensive understanding may be required to fully appreciate them.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One approach to the analysis of meaning is the distinction between form and content.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Content refers to what is presented, such as the depicted topic, expressed ideas, and conceptual messages.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Form refers to how the content is presented, such as medium, technique, composition, and style.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Form encompasses modes of presentation in different art forms, like color and spatial arrangement in painting, harmony and rhythm in music, and narrative voice and plot structure in literature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Representation is a depiction of real or imagined entities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, a portrait painting represents a person, and a fantasy novel represents an imaginary chain of events.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Similarity is a crucial element in many forms of artistic representation, meaning that the artwork resembles the depicted entity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Representation can also happen through other means, such as conventional symbols and established codes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It is particularly prevalent in certain art forms and styles, such as classical art and realism.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Since antiquity, representation has been a key concept in theories of art, such as Plato's idea of defining art as imitation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] However, it is controversial whether representation plays a central role in all art forms, including music and abstract modern art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Expression is the conveyance of psychological states, such as emotions, moods, and attitudes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, a painter may depict a barren landscape in muted colors to express sadness, and a musician might use a fast tempo and upbeat melody to convey excitement.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The expressed mental states often align with the artist's personal experience.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] However, this is not necessarily the case, and artists may explore psychological states they observed in others or entirely fictional experiences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An artwork can express a mental state like sadness by evoking it in the experience of the audience.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Alternatively, the expression can also happen if observers recognize the presence of sadness in the artwork even if they do not personally feel it.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Expression theories consider expression a core feature of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They characterize artworks as expressions of the artist's mind, focusing on creativity and originality in the manifestation of aesthetic experiences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The process of interpretation is the attempt to uncover the meaning of an artwork to understand its significance and value.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] In the widest sense, interpretation encompasses any way of assigning meaning, including obvious descriptions of depicted entities and explanations of literal word meanings.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Interpretations aim to discover underlying aspects that are relevant to the understanding and appreciation of the artwork.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The terms *interpretation* and *criticism* are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] However, criticism is typically associated with more components, like a general description of the criticized artwork and a classification of style and genre.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Criticism also explains the art-historical background and evaluates positive and negative qualities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Critics sometimes propose conflicting interpretations of the same artwork.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to critical monism, there is only one comprehensive correct interpretation, implying that conflicting interpretations cannot both be correct.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Critical pluralism, by contrast, asserts that there can be different but equally valid interpretations and that it is not always possible to determine which of two conflicting interpretations is superior.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A similar debate addresses whether interpretations can be true or false in an objective sense.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Several frameworks of interpretation have been proposed.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] According to intentionalism, the meaning of an artwork is determined by the author's intent—their reasons and motives that led to the creation of the artwork.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This typically involves analyzing the ideas the artist aimed to express but can also include a biographical analysis to learn about psychological and social circumstances in the artist's life.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Intentionalism is a controversial theory, termed the *intentional fallacy* by its critics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Some objections point to cases where the author's intention cannot be known, where the author cannot be identified, or where no traditional author exists, as in artworks created by artificial intelligence.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] In these cases, meaning would be inaccessible or non-existent.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Other objections assert that an artist may fail to accurately express their intention or may manifest unintended aesthetic features, suggesting that an artwork can contain both less and more than the artist intended.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] An alternative to intentionalism argues that meaning is determined by artistic, stylistic, linguistic, and other cultural conventions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For example, linguistic conventions determine the literal meanings of words and thereby influence the overall meaning of a poem.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Another framework holds that meaning is shaped by how the audience, rather than the author, interprets or would interpret the intention underlying the work.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Artistic formalism proposes a different approach by focusing interpretation exclusively on formal or perceptual features of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aestheticism and instrumentalism are theories about the value of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Aestheticism asserts that the primary value of art lies in its intrinsic aesthetic merits, independent of any external purposes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This idea of the autonomy of art is expressed in the slogan "art for art's sake".
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Strong forms of aestheticism not only disregard external purposes but see them as detrimental influences that undermine artistic integrity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Instrumentalism, by contrast, explains the value of art by the effects it has on other domains.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It understands art as a means to things such as moral education, spiritual growth, therapeutic benefits, and social cohesion.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The individual arts are practices or disciplines in the domain of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They encompass a wide range of fields, including traditionally established forms such as painting, music, and literature, as well as newer types like video games.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] One classification divides them into visual arts, literary arts, and performance arts.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The boundaries between these categories are not always clear, and alternative classifications have been proposed.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Painting is a visual art in which a painter applies colors to a surface.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It allows for a diverse range of motives and styles, and is often considered a paradigm form of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The representation of real entities plays a central role in many forms of painting, ranging from landscapes and people to historic events.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This process involves artistic choices that go beyond simple replication, such as guiding the viewer's attention to specific aspects or highlighting important but easily overlooked features.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The issue of representation is also crucial in photography, a visual art shaped by technological developments in camera design and editing processes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A key topic in the philosophy of photography concerns its mechanical manner of authentically representing real objects, frequently drawing parallels and distinctions with painting.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The status of photographs as true artworks is disputed, with critics arguing that the mechanical nature of capturing images lacks the necessary artistic creativity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Music is a performance art in which sounds are combined to create aesthetic patterns, relying on aspects such as melody and rhythm.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Unlike painting and photography, it is typically less associated with objective representation and more closely linked to the expression of emotions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] A key discussion in the philosophy of music concerns the definition of music or the criteria under which a combination of sounds qualifies as music.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Proposals range from objective criteria, such as the patterns of how sounds are organized, to subjective criteria, focusing on audience experience and interpretation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Dance is another performance art in which dancers create aesthetic patterns through a series of bodily movements, often following a choreography.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It is typically accompanied by music and shares with music an emphasis on expressive features.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Architecture is the art or craft of designing and building, encompassing a wide range of structures from monuments and cathedrals to skyscrapers and residential homes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It typically combines aesthetic with functional goals, seeking to create buildings that are both visually appealing and practically useful.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] This dual nature is a central topic of the philosophy of architecture, with one theory suggesting that mere buildings can be distinguished from artistic architecture by the presence of decorative elements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Sculpture is another art form that, like architecture, involves the creation of three-dimensional works.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Sculptures are usually static objects made of robust materials like stone, metal, and wood, but may also include dynamic elements, as is the case for kinetic sculptures.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Key discussions in the philosophy of sculpture address the definition, representational aspects, and aesthetic features of sculptures as well as the influence of the chosen material.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Literature has language as its primary medium.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] In its widest sense, literature encompasses any written document.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] However, the term is typically used in a narrower sense in aesthetics for forms of writing that belong to the high arts, such as poems, novels, and drama.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Literature as an art is often characterized by its deliberate, elaborate, and organized use of language, but there is no universally accepted demarcation between artistic literature and other forms of writing.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Poetry is a distinct form of literature often written in verses composed of several lines that may follow specific patterns, such as meter and rhyme.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Many poems are characterized by an economical use of language that seeks to evoke specific experiences while being difficult to paraphrase.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Theater is a performance art that combines elements from other art forms.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] It typically includes a carefully prepared set or stage where actors perform, usually incorporating storytelling and sound design to create immersive experiences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Theater is performed before a live audience, which can create a sense of immediacy that is less prevalent in related art forms, such as film.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Film also integrates aspects from several artistic disciplines but relies more heavily on technological means of recording and editing.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Films can involve actors but may also include animated characters or document real-life events.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They are normally the result of collaborative efforts of many people, which complicates the identification of a singular author in the traditional sense.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Video games are a more recent form of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Like theater and film, they usually blend visual, auditory, and narrative elements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] They typically stand out through their emphasis on player interaction, allowing active exploration of and engagement with the game world.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] The status of films and video games as serious forms of art is disputed.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] Proponents tend to emphasize their aesthetic qualities; critics often point to their association with mass production and popular culture as counterarguments.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p01] For video games, a related debate centers on the elements of competition and winning, questioning whether these elements run counter to the spirit of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Aesthetic phenomena are investigated in several fields.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Some areas examine the relationship between aesthetics and other branches of philosophy or compare different artistic traditions; others study aesthetic elements in everyday life or engage in scientific inquiry using empirical methods.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Ethics is the branch of philosophy that studies moral phenomena in general and right behavior in particular.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Artworks can have ethical consequences by influencing how people feel, perceive, and evaluate their circumstances.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, artworks can glorify violence and reinforce biases, just as they can inspire empathy and challenge societal norms.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] As a result, art is also relevant to the field of politics since it can steer political sentiment to legitimize authority or mobilize resistance, thereby influencing voter attitudes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Artworks can also explore morally relevant topics without expressing a clear positive or negative evaluation, such as a novel examining an ethical dilemma without favoring one solution over the others.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Since both ethics and aesthetics deal with values, philosophers seek to clarify the relationship between moral and aesthetic values, proposing several theories of their interaction.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Ethicism asserts that the moral value of an artwork can increase its aesthetic value, while ethical defects may undermine its artistic merit.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This view is reversed by immoralism, which suggests that in some cases, moral flaws enhance aesthetic experience.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Autonomism rejects both positions, arguing that these domains of evaluation are independent.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Scientific approaches rooted in psychology and related fields employ empirical methods to conduct inquiries and justify hypotheses.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The psychology of aesthetics examines the mental processes involved in the perception and appreciation of beauty and art, using methods such as experimentation, observation, and surveys.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Experimental aesthetics is an early and influential approach pioneered by Gustav Fechner.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It follows a bottom-up methodology that starts with human sensation, investigating preferences to simple physical stimuli, such as basic colors and shapes.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Gestalt psychology relies on a more holistic outlook, examining how composition and object placement influence aesthetic experience, like the relationship between balanced organization and a sense of calm.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Some works, such as Daniel Berlyne's approach, shift the focus from perception to emotion, suggesting that features like novelty and complexity cause arousal and that the right amount of arousal is pleasurable.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Psychological analysis also examines the temporal structure of aesthetic experiences of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] One outlook identifies two phases: an initial impression in which the observer forms a rough general idea of the artwork's topic, structure, and meaning, followed by a focal analysis of more specific features.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Research further explores how circumstances influence aesthetic experience, like the contrast between encountering a painting in a museum or a shopping mall.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Along with physical circumstances, social and personal factors also influence aesthetic experience, such as group dynamics, prior knowledge, and the motivation for seeking the experience.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Evolutionary psychology analyzes mental phenomena as products of natural selection.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It asserts that genetic variations responsible for new capacities are passed on to future generations if they enhance survival and reproduction.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Adopting this approach, evolutionary aesthetics interprets beauty and other aesthetic experiences as adaptive traits that guide fitness-relevant preferences.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Examples are aesthetic preferences for environments conducive to survival, such as landscapes resembling the African savanna, and sexual selection by identifying genetically fit mates.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] By focusing on the relatively permanent biological nature of humans, evolutionary psychology sees aesthetic values as universal or transcultural patterns of taste and appreciation, contrasting with subjectivist theories that understand aesthetic values as cultural constructs.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Neuroaesthetics applies neuroscientific insights and methods to study the relationship between brain activity and aesthetic experience.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Aesthetic experiences arise from brain processes responsible for organizing sensory stimuli, forming cognitive interpretations, and generating emotional responses.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Neuroaesthetics examines these processes using empirical methods, including neuroimaging techniques like fMRI.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In one type of experiment, participants view artworks, some considered beautiful and others ugly, with researchers noting that the brain area known as the orbitofrontal cortex is more active when viewing beautiful paintings.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Cognitive science, another field, employs an interdisciplinary approach to study mental phenomena by examining how they access and transform information.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] An influential theory, suggested by Ernst Gombrich, analyzes aesthetic experience through the interplay of low-level and high-level information processes: sensory processes provide low-level information, which is organized and interpreted using high-level conceptual background knowledge.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Another approach analyzes aesthetic representation through the modularity of mind—the hypothesis that the mind is composed of mental modules that function independently.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It argues that paintings represent real objects by triggering the same mental modules responsible for the recognition of those objects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Comparative aesthetics examines diverse aesthetic traditions, analyzing the similarities and differences in their standards of beauty and theoretical approaches.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, the focus in Western aesthetics on high art and its separation from everyday affairs is not common in most other traditions, for which art is typically closely integrated with practical functions in everyday life, including religion and moral education.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Artistic differences between different traditions also encompass dominant media, common styles, and chosen motifs.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The comparison of cultural products from different traditions presents conceptual challenges associated with tradition-specific aesthetic concepts and standards of evaluation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The uncritical application of standards from one tradition to evaluate the works of another can result in cultural imperialism.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] At the same time, these differences provide opportunities to artists and philosophers to incorporate new elements and explore novel perspectives.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Indian aesthetics draws a close connection between artistic activity and religious practice.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It argues that artistic expression is a spiritual endeavor that should be informed by knowledge of the self and reality, express devotion to the divine, and avoid attachments to the fruits of the activity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Traditional Indian aesthetics analyzes art in terms of basic life emotions, called rasas, such as delight, humor, sadness, and anger.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It sees art as a play that imitates reality by conveying experiences of the rasas.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Its focus is on the universal expressions of human emotional life rather than person-specific feelings.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This school of thought identifies artistic creativity as the ability to harness the full potential of the medium, like colors, sounds, and words, to convey experiential universals.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For the audience, it recommends an aesthetic attitude characterized by a psychic distance from private concerns to transcend the personal self and become receptive to universal elements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Chinese aesthetics emphasizes the spontaneous nature of artistic creativity and its connection to the moral and spiritual domains.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It argues that art should foster harmony within society and align with the natural order of the universe.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In this role, art is both self-expression and self-cultivation aimed at promoting social well-being.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The main focus of Chinese aesthetics is on poetry, painting, and calligraphy, known as the three perfections.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This tradition influenced Japanese aesthetics, which is characterized by its interest in nature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Different art styles in this tradition are shaped by religious outlooks, particularly Shinto and Buddhism.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Japanese theories of art stress the interrelation between the experience of the artist and the response of the audience.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Islamic philosophers see art as a means of communicating philosophical and religious truths, making them accessible to the general public without requiring abstract theoretical thought.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Thinkers such as Al-Farabi and Avicenna argued that imagination rather than reasoning underlies artistic creation and appreciation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] According to this view, art imitates reality and evokes emotions to convey underlying truths and positively influence behavior.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Religious teachings play a central role in Islamic aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, the belief that Allah is transcendent and boundless has resulted in the avoidance of figurative depictions and the emphasis on abstract art forms.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] African aesthetics emphasizes the intuitive and emotional nature of art, highlighting its communal function in social life.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Early scholarship on this tradition was typically conducted from an ethnocentric perspective using Western aesthetic standards to interpret and evaluate African art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This usually resulted in the portrayal of African artworks as exotic curiosities that lack the sophistication of high art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The emergence of indigenous scholarship in the 20th century sought to correct this interpretation, arguing that the emphasis on moral, emotional, and intuitive aspects reflects different artistic standards rather than a deficiency.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This school of thought, often associated with the concept of Négritude, focuses on the importance of feelings in contrast to abstraction and intellectual analysis.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Environmental aesthetics deals with the appreciation of nature, including elements such as forests, mountain ranges, rivers, and flowers.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It encompasses both transient appearances, such as the fleeting beauty of a landscape during sunset, and enduring aspects, such as the majesty of a centuries-old tree.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This field focuses on sensory and formal qualities associated with beauty and related aesthetic qualities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In this respect, it contrasts with the philosophy of art, which typically emphasizes the interpretation of underlying meanings associated with expression and representation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Some approaches to environmental aesthetics also consider the impact of background knowledge on the aesthetic experience of nature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For instance, ecological awareness of the intricate relationships within an ecosystem can shape the appreciation of a woodland environment by understanding it as a habitat of diverse species.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In its broadest sense, environmental aesthetics encompasses the appreciation of any environment, including those created by humans.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This inquiry is closely associated with everyday aesthetics, which examines aesthetic phenomena encountered in daily life.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Everyday aesthetics covers both public and private environments, ranging from modern cities and industrial sites to private homes and backyards, as well as personal adornments and consumer products, such as clothing, hairstyles, industrial design, and web design.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The aesthetics of popular art, a related discipline, investigates aesthetic qualities in popular culture and compares the evaluative standards of popular art with those of high or fine art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, it studies the contrast between commercial mass art and experimental avant-garde and explores specific types of popular art, such as kitsch.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Art plays a central role in the field of religion and manifests in many forms, including paintings, sculptures, architecture, music, dance, and literature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Its key characteristic comes from its religious function, such as conveying theological and moral teachings, representing symbolic truths, inspiring religious experiences, and aiding devotional practices.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Religious art is part of all major religions and was the dominant art form during ancient and medieval times.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Its influence began to wane in the modern period due to secularization.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This shift is also reflected in developments in the philosophy of art that introduced a focus on disinterestedness and the autonomy of aesthetic experience from external purposes, including religious goals.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Several theories of aesthetics are associated with specific philosophical schools of thought.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Marxist aesthetics examines the relationship between art, class structure, and social ideology, exploring how art can enforce or challenge established power hierarchies.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Feminist aesthetics criticizes male biases in aesthetic theory and artistic practice while discussing alternatives.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It investigates unfair social institutions and aesthetic standards that disadvantage women and exclude them from the art world.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] An example is the male gaze—a cultural phenomenon that treats women as objects of male spectatorship rather than as artistic creators.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Postmodern aesthetics is a diverse movement that challenges established concepts and theories in the field of aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It typically rejects the focus on disinterested pleasure, the autonomy of art from other domains, and the distinction between high and popular art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It tends to promote a pluralism that embraces diversity, playfulness, and irony.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The term mathematical beauty refers to aesthetic qualities of abstract mathematical concepts and theories.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For instance, a mathematical proof may be considered beautiful if it demonstrates a profound insight in an effective manner or reveals an underlying unity of seemingly disparate mathematical ideas.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The aesthetics of science examines aesthetic judgments about scientific theories and practices, including the role of beauty and creativity in the construction of models.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Computer art involves the use of computers in the creation of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It can take many forms, ranging from minor digital enhancements of existing artworks to entirely new creations generated using complex algorithms.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Its abstract nature, based on symbolic representation and manipulation of electronic signals, distinguishes computer art from traditional forms of art, which rely on more tangible media.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This medium offers new artistic possibilities, such as virtual reality and interactivity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Rapid developments in artificial intelligence in the 21st century have significantly impacted computer art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] They include the emergence of generative models—systems that are trained using existing media to create new texts, images, music, or videos in response to verbal descriptions of the intended result.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Examples include ChatGPT, Stable Diffusion, MuseNet, and RunwayML.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Meta-aesthetics examines the fundamental assumptions and concepts underlying aesthetics.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It asks about the existence of aesthetic facts, the meaning of aesthetic statements, and the ways of acquiring aesthetic knowledge.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] A central meta-aesthetic debate between realism and anti-realism addresses whether there are mind-independent aesthetic facts.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] A related discussion between cognitivism and non-cognitivism considers whether aesthetic statements can be objectively true or primarily express personal emotions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Aesthetics has its roots in ancient thought, which typically interpreted beauty as a metaphysical phenomenon associated with the order of the cosmos.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In ancient Greek philosophy, early explorations of the nature of beauty are found in Pythagorean philosophy in the 5th and 4th centuries BCE.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This tradition proposed that beauty arises from the proportion and harmony between different elements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In works like the *Philebus* and *Symposium*, Plato (427–347 BCE) analyzed pure beauty as an immutable form that exists independently of matter.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He argued that material entities are beautiful if they participate in the form of beauty.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Plato understood art as a craft that seeks to imitate and represent material entities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He acknowledged that art has some didactic value but was overall critical of it, asserting that its derivative nature, based on imitation of sensible features, cannot lead to true knowledge.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) examined aesthetics through the lens of poetry, providing a detailed analysis in his book *Poetics*.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He agreed with Plato's idea that art is a form of imitation but adopted a more positive outlook, proposing that it can reveal universal truths.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Aristotle suggested that successful artistic imitation is pleasurable and can have therapeutic or cathartic effects.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] By linking this pleasure to beauty, he tried to explain why the imitation of unpleasurable phenomena, like tragic stories, can be enjoyable.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Also influenced by Plato, Plotinus (204–270 CE) argued that beauty is not based on sensory symmetries or simple proportions but embodies an underlying order, harmony, and unity associated with the ultimate source of creation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In ancient India, the Natya Shastra, traditionally attributed to Bharata (c.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] 200 CE), formulated the rasa theory of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This theory posits that the goal of art is to convey fundamental life emotions as experiential universals of human existence.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In ancient China, the philosophy of art was shaped by Confucianism.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It emphasized self-cultivation and the relation between nature and human culture.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] During the medieval period, the rise of Christianity led Western aesthetic thinkers to blend ancient Greek thought with religious teachings, often in the form of philosophical theology.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Influenced by Plato and Plotinus, Augustine of Hippo (354–430 CE) explored the distinction between artistic creation, which transforms matter, and divine creation, which brings forth existence out of nothing.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He thought that all beauty originates from God and analyzed it in terms of unity, equality, number, proportion, and order.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Thomas Aquinas defined beauty as what brings pleasure upon perception.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For him, the mind plays a central role in this process since beauty lies in the immaterial form of the perceived object that the mind recognizes in the sensory data.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Aquinas saw beauty as a basic category of being and identified it with proportion, radiance, and integrity.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] An integration of Greek philosophy and religious thought also happened in the Islamic world.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] 950 CE) associated beauty with pleasure and understood it as a degree of perfection and a divine attribute of Allah.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] 980 – 1037 CE) distinguished sensible from intelligible beauty and explored psychological processes underlying aesthetic judgments, such as the role of imagination.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Meanwhile, in India, the rasa theory of art expanded to also encompass devotional practices, including efforts to portray or evoke profound religious experiences of the union with the divine.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] 1025 CE) elaborated the spiritual dimension of the rasa theory, drawing a sharp distinction between ordinary worldly emotions and rasas as transcendent aesthetic emotions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] 5th to 6th centuries CE) combined Daoist and Confucian ideas, suggesting that artists align with the natural order of the universe and spontaneously express the movement of life in their artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He also proposed a set of basic principles of painting.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] 1090 CE) argued that artworks reflect the moral character and spiritual outlook of the artist, which he saw as a central factor of the artwork's aesthetic value.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] During this period, the growing influence of Buddhism on Chinese aesthetic thought led to an artistic shift from objective reality to subjective experiences as a result of Buddhist teachings on the illusory nature of reality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The medieval period in the West came to an end with the emergence of the Renaissance starting in the 15th century.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This change led to the revival of classical aesthetic ideals while secularization paved the way for rationalist inquiries into general laws of beauty and empiricist analyses of sensory and emotional experiences in the subsequent Age of Enlightenment.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Modern aesthetics emerged in the 18th century, as philosophers engaged more systematically with the subject.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] A key step in this process happened through the philosophy of Alexander Baumgarten (1714–1762), who first conceived aesthetics as a distinct field of inquiry: the science of sensory cognitions or the study of what is sensed and imagined.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In British philosophy, Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) followed ideas of the third Earl of Shaftesbury (1671–1713) and provided an early theory of taste, conceptualizing it as an internal sense responsible for aesthetic apprehension.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This outlook inspired David Hume (1711–1776) to develop a subjective theory of beauty, understanding it as a pleasurable sentiment caused by perceptions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He combined this perspective with the idea that beauty follows intersubjective standards as shared principles of taste governing which objects are experienced as beautiful.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) expanded Hume's idea that aesthetic judgments are both subjective and universal, arguing that the underlying pleasure must be disinterested to follow universal standards.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] According to Kant, this type of pleasure comes from a free play in which the mental faculties of imagination and understanding harmoniously interact.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In response to earlier theories by Edmund Burke (1729–1797), Kant also examined the sublime as a distinct aesthetic quality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Kant's thought inspired diverse developments in German philosophy.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Friedrich Schiller (1759–1805) saw art as a unifying phenomenon that synthesizes different basic human drives in a type of play.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] J. von Schelling (1775–1854) shared a similar perspective, arguing that art reconciles opposites and reveals the underlying unity of the self and nature.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Hegel (1770–1831) studied aesthetics through his philosophical system of absolute idealism, seeing artistic beauty as the sensory manifestation of truth.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Combining Kantian and Indian philosophy, Arthur Schopenhauer (1788–1860) understood disinterested aesthetic experience as a suspension of the will, resulting in a temporary peace of mind by interrupting the cycle of striving and suffering.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He inspired the Chinese philosopher Wang Guowei (1877–1927), who integrated Schopenhauer's ideas with Buddhist thought.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Wang viewed the goal of art as the creation of worlds within the world, which are open to disinterested reflection.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Friedrich Nietzsche (1844–1900) rejected the disinterestedness of aesthetic experience and the autonomy of art from other domains.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Instead, he considered art an expression of the struggle between opposing life forces, seeing it as a vehicle of transformation and life affirmation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Following the thought of Karl Marx (1818–1883), Marxist aesthetic philosophers like Leon Trotsky (1879–1940) and Georg Lukács (1885–1971) examined how art reflects and shapes social ideologies and power hierarchies.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Drawing from Marxist ideas, Theodor Adorno (1903–1969) critiqued the commodification of art and explored its ability to express alienation and challenge societal norms.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Also adopting a Marxist perspective, Walter Benjamin (1892–1940) studied how advances in technological reproducibility transform art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Romanticist thought emphasized artistic originality, creativity, and the expression of profound feelings, as formulated in the works of J.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It saw artworks as products of human genius that defy rule-based understanding.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This school of thought inspired the theory of expressionism, which asserts that the primary function of art is to communicate emotions and other mental states.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It was examined by thinkers such as Leo Tolstoy (1828–1910), Benedetto Croce (1866–1952), and R.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Intentionalism, a closely related position, focuses on the author's intent as the source of meaning of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Monroe Beardsley (1915–1985) opposed this view, arguing that meaning is not fixed by private intentions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Sigmund Freud (1856–1939) and Carl Jung (1875–1961) interpreted art through a psychoanalytic perspective as expressions of the unconscious, an approach also later explored by Richard Wollheim (1923–2005).
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, aestheticism became a prominent view in English-speaking philosophy.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, Walter Pater (1839–1894) and Oscar Wilde (1854–1900) proposed that art is an end in itself without an ulterior purpose.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Pragmatists rejected this outlook and the idea that aesthetic experience is disinterested.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For instance, John Dewey (1859–1952) proposed in his 1934 book *Art as Experience* that the value of art lies in the unique experiences it provides, which can lead to individual and societal improvements.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Formalism became another influential theory of art in the early 20th century.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] It dismisses the focus on expressive and representational aspects and argues instead that artworks are defined by formal features, like the arrangement of perceptual qualities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Clive Bell (1881–1964), a major proponent of this view, termed this arrangement "significant form".
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The emergence of Dadaism and conceptual art challenged traditional definitions of art based on intrinsic features of artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Danto (1924–2013) and George Dickie (1926–2020) to propose institutional definitions, arguing that social conventions set by the art world determine which objects are artworks.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Mary Mothersill (1923–2008) challenged these developments.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] She aimed to restore earlier conceptions of beauty associated with Aquinas, Hume, and Kant, focusing on the apprehension of aesthetic qualities.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] In continental philosophy, the school of phenomenology studied the immediate experience of art.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, it examined how artworks can depict unreal objects, how imagination is involved in the process, and how art can reveal features of reality.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] This tradition is closely related to existentialist aesthetics, which views artworks as expressions of human freedom that can authentically portray central aspects of the human condition.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] The philosophy of Martin Heidegger (1889–1976) influenced both traditions.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] He criticized the focus on disinterested pleasure found in modern philosophy of art, arguing that artworks can reveal truths about human existence and provide new perspectives of understanding.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Heidegger's student Hans-Georg Gadamer (1900–2002) further investigated the relation between art and truth, examining aesthetic experience and traditional theories through phenomenological analysis and hermeneutic interpretation.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Postmodern thinkers, like Roland Barthes (1915–1980) and Jacques Derrida (1930–2004), challenged the separation of art from everyday life and the idea that artworks have a stable meaning or universal value.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] They suggested instead that artistic merit depends on historical and cultural contexts.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] Starting in the 1970s, feminist perspectives challenged male-centric theories and practices within aesthetic philosophy and the art world.
[src:aesthetics/aesthetics-p02] For example, Simone de Beauvoir (1908–1986) and Luce Irigaray (born 1930) explored how feminine perspectives are marginalized by masculine standards.
